r=Seaby |location=London |isbn=1-85264-047-2 |ref=W2 }}\n*{{cite book |last=Woolf |first=A |author-link=Alex Woolf |year=2007 |title=From Pictland to Alba, 789\u20131070 |series=The New Edinburgh History of Scotland |publisher=Edinburgh University Press |location=Edinburgh |isbn=978-0-7486-1233-8 |ref=W1 }}\n*{{cite book |last=Woolf |first=A |year=2009 |chapter=Scotland |editor-last=Stafford |editor-first=P |editor-link=Pauline Stafford |title=A Companion to the Early Middle Ages: Britain and Ireland, c.500\u2013c.1100 |series=Blackwell Companions to British History |publisher=Blackwell Publishing |location=Chichester |pages=251\u2013267 |isbn=978-1-405-10628-3 |ref=W4 }}\n*{{cite book |last=Woolf |first=A |year=2010 |chapter=Reporting Scotland in the Anglo-Saxon Chronicle |pages=221\u2013239 |editor-last=Jorgensen |editor-first=A |title=Reading the Anglo-Saxon Chronicle: Language, Literature, History |series=Studies in the Early Middle Ages |publisher=[[Brepols Publishers]] |location=Turnhout |isbn=978-2-503-52394-1 |doi=10.1484/M.SEM-EB.3.4457 |ref=W6 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|M\u00e1el Coluim mac Domnaill}}\n*{{PASE|12540|Malcolm 4}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou |||||997|name=M\u00e1el Coluim}}\n{{s-reg}}\n|-<!---This line is a workaround for a bug in template s-vac--->\n{{s-vac |unknown |unknlast=[[Dyfnwal ab Owain]]<sup>1</sup>}}\n{{s-ttl |title=[[King of Strathclyde]]}}\n{{s-aft |after=[[Owain ap Dyfnwal (died 1015)|Owain ap Dyfnwal]]}}\n{{s-ref |Whilst it is possible that M\u00e1el Coluim succeeded Dyfnwal, another possibility is that Dyfnwal was earlier succeeded by [[Rhydderch ap Dyfnwal]].}}\n\n{{Kings of Strathclyde}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mael Coluim King of Strathclyde}}\n[[Category:10th-century Scottish monarchs]]\n[[Category:997 deaths]]\n[[Category:Monarchs of Strathclyde]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox royalty\n| name         = M\u00e1el Coluim\n| title        = [[King of Strathclyde]]\n| image        = File:M\u00e1el Coluim mac Domnaill (British Library Cotton MS Domitian A VIII, folio 5v).jpg\n| alt          = Refer to caption\n| caption      = M\u00e1el Coluim's name and title as it appears on folio 5v of British Library Cotton Domitian A VIII (''[[De primo Saxonum adventu]]''): \"{{lang|la|Malcolm rex Cumbrorum}}\".<ref>[[#D4|Davidson (2002)]] p. 142 n. 149; [[#AA2|Arnold (1885)]] p. 372; [[#C13|''Cotton MS Domitian A VIII'' (n.d.)]].</ref>\n| predecessor  = [[Dyfnwal ab Owain]] or [[Rhydderch ap Dyfnwal]]\n| successor    = [[Owain ap Dyfnwal (died 1015)|Owain ap Dyfnwal]]\n| death_date   = 997\n| issue        = [[Owain Foel]]?\n| father       = Dyfnwal ab Owain\n}}\n\n'''M\u00e1el Coluim''' (died 997) was a tenth-century [[King of Strathclyde]].{{#tag:ref|Since the 2000s academics have accorded M\u00e1el Coluim various personal names in English secondary sources: ''Mael Colaim'',<ref>[[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]].</ref> ''M\u00e1el Coluim'',<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]]; [[#E1|Edmonds (2014)]]; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]]; [[#O2|Oram (2011)]]; [[#AX1|Aird (2009)]]; [[#D4|Davidson (2002)]]; [[#H5|Hudson (1996)]].</ref> ''Mael Coluim'',<ref>[[#M10|Minard (2012)]]; [[#P1|Parsons (2011)]]; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]]; [[#B12|Busse (2006c)]]; [[#M6|Minard (2006)]]; [[#B11|Broun (2004c)]]; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]]; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]].</ref> ''Maelcoluim'',<ref>[[#D2|Duncan (2002)]].</ref> and ''Malcolm''.<ref>[[#W10|Williams (2014)]]; [[#W14|Walker (2013)]]; [[#C7|Clarkson (2012)]]; [[#M10|Minard (2012)]]; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]]; [[#KB1|Keynes (2008)]]; [[#BXX5|Breeze (2007)]]; [[#M3|Macquarrie (2004)]]; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]]; [[#D2|Duncan (2002)]]; [[#H9|Hudson (2002)]]; [[#J2|Jayakumar (2002)]].</ref> Since the 2000s academics have accorded M\u00e1el Coluim various [[patronyms]] in English secondary sources: ''M\u00e1el Coluim mac Domnaill'',<ref>[[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]].</ref> and ''Malcolm ap Dyfnwal''.<ref>[[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]].</ref>|group=note}} He was a younger son of [[Dyfnwal ab Owain, King of Strathclyde]], and thus a member of the Cumbrian dynasty that had ruled the kingdom for generations. M\u00e1el Coluim's [[Gaelic languages|Gaelic]] name could indicate that he was born during either an era of amiable relations with the Scots, or else during a period of Scottish overlordship. In 945, the [[Edmund I, King of the English]] invaded the kingdom, and appears to have granted the Scots permission to dominate the Cumbrians. The English king is further reported to have blinded several of M\u00e1el Coluim's brothers in an act that could have been an attempt to deprive Dyfnwal of an heir.\n\nIt is unknown when Dyfnwal's reign came to an end. There is reason to suspect that a certain [[Rhydderch ap Dyfnwal]] was a son of his, and that this man ruled when he assassinated the reigning [[King of Alba]] in 971. Certainly by 973, M\u00e1el Coluim was associated with the kingship, as both he and his father are recorded to have been participated in a remarkable meeting of kings assembled by [[Edgar, King of the English]]. The context of this assembly is not entirely clear. It could have concerned the stability of the border between the [[Kingdom of England|English realm]] and that of the [[Kingdom of Alba|Scots]] and Cumbrians. It could have also focused upon lurking threat of [[Vikings]] based in [[Kingdom of Dublin|Dublin]] and [[Kingdom of the Isles|the Isles]].\n\nM\u00e1el Coluim's father died in 975, having set off upon a pilgrimage to Rome. Quite when M\u00e1el Coluim succeeded Dyfnwal is uncertain. It could have been before, during, or after the assembly of 973. In any case, M\u00e1el Coluim's reign was evidently unremarkable, although the tenth-century ''[[Saltair na Rann]]'' preserves several lines of verse in his praise. M\u00e1el Coluim appears to have been succeeded by a brother, [[Owain ap Dyfnwal (died 1015)|Owain]]. This man's successor, [[Owain Foel]], seems to have been a son of M\u00e1el Coluim.\n\n==Dyfnwal's sons and English aggression==\n\n[[File:M\u00e1el Coluim, King of Strathclyde (map).png|right|thumb|upright|alt=Map of Britain|Locations relating to M\u00e1el Coluim's life and times.]]\n\nM\u00e1el Coluim was a son of [[Dyfnwal ab Owain, King of Strathclyde]],<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. genealogical tables; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] p. 572 fig. 17.4; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. genealogical tables; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 238 tab. 6.4; [[#B11|Broun (2004c)]] p. 135 tab.; [[#M2|Macquarrie (1998)]] pp. 6, 16; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 173 genealogy 6.</ref> a man who ruled the Cumbrian [[Kingdom of Strathclyde]] from about the 930s to the 970s.<ref>[[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 67.</ref> M\u00e1el Coluim's name is [[Gaelic languages|Gaelic]], and may be evidence of a marriage alliance between his family and the neighbouring [[Alp\u00ednid dynasty]] of the [[Kingdom of Alba]].<ref>[[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 44.</ref> The name may also reveal that M\u00e1el Coluim was a [[godson]] of his northern namesake, [[M\u00e1el Coluim mac Domnaill, King of Alba]], and could perhaps be indicative of Dyfnwal's submission to this Scottish king.<ref>[[#P1|Parsons (2011)]] p. 129; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 184.</ref>{{#tag:ref|The Gaelic personal name {{lang|mga|M\u00e1el Coluim}} means \"servant of [[St Columba]]\". This name was borne by [[M\u00e1el Coluim, son of the king of the Cumbrians]], a man who appears to have been a member of the Strathclyde dynasty, and may well have been a descendant of M\u00e1el Coluim himself.<ref>[[#C1001|Clarkson (2013)]] p. 25.</ref> The [[Welsh language|Welsh]] personal name {{lang|cy|Dyfnwal}} is a [[cognate]] of the Gaelic {{lang|mga|Domnall}}.<ref>[[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] pp. xiii, 184, 184 n. 17; [[#K1|Koch (2006)]]; [[#B3|Bruford (2000)]] pp. 64, 65 n. 76; [[#S11|Schrijver (1995)]] p. 81.</ref>|group=note}}\n\n[[File:Edmund I - MS Royal 14 B VI.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Refer to caption|Depiction of [[Edmund I]] as it appears on folio 2r of British Library Royal 14 B VI.<ref>[[#R1001|''Royal MS 14 B VI'' (n.d.)]].</ref>]]\n\nIn 945, the \"A\" version of the eleventh- to thirteenth-century ''[[Annales Cambri\u00e6]]'',<ref>[[#G2|Gough-Cooper (2015a)]] p. 27 \u00a7 a509.3; [[#K2|Keynes (2015)]] pp. 95\u201396; [[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 \u00b6 14, 6 n. 19; [[#H11|Halloran (2011)]] p. 308, 308 n. 40; [[#W6|Woolf (2010)]] p. 228, 228 n. 27; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] p. 153; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 183; [[#D3|Downham (2003)]] p. 42; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] p. 39; [[#A10|Alcock (1975\u20131976)]] p. 106; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 449.</ref> and the thirteenth- and fourteenth-century ''[[Brut y Tywysogyon]]'' reveal that the Kingdom of Strathclyde was wasted by the English.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 \u00b6 15; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 25; [[#D3|Downham (2003)]] p. 42; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] p. 39; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 449; [[#R1|Rh\u0177s (1890)]] p. 261; [[#W7|Williams Ab Ithel (1860)]] pp. 20\u201321.</ref> The ninth- to twelfth-century ''[[Anglo-Saxon Chronicle]]'' offers more information, and relates that [[Edmund I, King of the English]] harried across the land of the Cumbrians, and {{lang|ang|let}} the region to M\u00e1el Coluim mac Domnaill.<ref>[[#G2|Gough-Cooper (2015a)]] p. 27 n. 191; [[#K2|Keynes (2015)]] pp. 95\u201396; [[#M4|McGuigan (2015)]] pp. 83, 139\u2013140; [[#M8|McLeod (2015)]] p. 4; [[#M5|Molyneaux (2015)]] pp. 33, 52\u201353, 76; [[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] chs. 1 \u00b6 10, 6 \u00b6 11, 6 n. 18, 6 \u00b6 20; [[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 5; [[#H11|Halloran (2011)]] p. 307, 307 n. 36; [[#M7|Molyneaux (2011)]] pp. 66, 66 n. 27, 69, 70, 73, 88; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6\u00b6 25\u201327; [[#W6|Woolf (2010)]] p. 228, 228 n. 26; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] p. 153; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 183; [[#C11|Clancy (2006)]]; [[#W13|Williams (2004b)]]; [[#D3|Downham (2003)]] p. 42; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] p. 16 n. 35; [[#D2|Duncan (2002)]] p. 23; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 78, 78 n. 114; [[#O1|O'Keeffe (2001)]] p. 80; [[#W5|Williams (1999)]] p. 86; [[#W9|Whitelock (1996)]] p. 224; [[#S9|Smyth (1989)]] pp. 205\u2013206; [[#A10|Alcock (1975\u20131976)]] p. 106; [[#S8|Stenton (1963)]] p. 355; [[#A5|Anderson, AO (1908)]] p. 74, 74 n. 3; [[#T6|Thorpe (1861)]] pp. 212\u2013213.</ref> Similarly, the twelfth-century ''[[Historia Anglorum (Henry of Huntingdon)|Historia Anglorum]]'' records that the English ravaged the realm, and that Edmund commended the lands to M\u00e1el Coluim mac Domnaill who had agreed to assist him by land and sea.<ref>[[#H10|Holland (2016)]] ch. Malmesbury \u00b6 7; [[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 \u00b6 11, 6 n. 20; [[#A5|Anderson, AO (1908)]] p. 74 nn. 4\u20135; [[#A4|Arnold (1879)]] p. 162 bk. 5 ch. 21; [[#F2|Forester (1853)]] p. 172 bk. 5.</ref> According to the version of events preserved by the thirteenth-century [[Flores historiarum (Wendover)|Wendover]]<ref>[[#F3|Firth (2016)]] pp. 24\u201325; [[#M4|McGuigan (2015)]] p. 139; [[#M5|Molyneaux (2015)]] pp. 33, 61, 76; [[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 \u00b6\u00b6 12\u201313, 6 n. 21; [[#H11|Halloran (2011)]] p. 308; [[#M7|Molyneaux (2011)]] pp. 66, 66 n. 27, 70; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 183; [[#D2|Duncan (2002)]] p. 23; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 78, 78 n. 114; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 174 n. 12; [[#S8|Stenton (1963)]] p. 355; [[#A5|Anderson, AO (1908)]] p. 74 n. 5; [[#G3|Giles (1849)]] pp. 252\u2013253; [[#C5|Coxe (1841)]] p. 398.</ref> and [[Flores historiarum (Paris)|Paris]] versions of ''Flores historiarum'', Edmund had two of Dyfnwal's sons blinded.<ref>[[#M4|McGuigan (2015)]] p. 139; [[#L1|Luard (2012)]] p. 500; [[#H11|Halloran (2011)]] p. 308, 308 n. 41; [[#Y1|Yonge (1853)]] p. 473.</ref> If these sources are to be believed, they could reveal that the two princes had been English hostages before hostilities broke out, or that they were prisoners captured in the midst of the campaign.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 \u00b6 14; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 25.</ref> The ritual blinding of kings was not an unknown act in contemporary Britain and Ireland,<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 n. 23.</ref> and it is possible that Edmund may have meant to deprive Dyfnwal of a royal heir.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] chs. 6 \u00b6 14, 7 \u00b6 5.</ref>\n\nThe gruesome fate inflicted upon Dyfnwal's sons could reveal that their father was regarded to have broken certain pledges rendered to the English.<ref>[[#H10|Holland (2016)]] ch. Malmesbury \u00b6 5; [[#M5|Molyneaux (2015)]] pp. 77\u201378; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 183.</ref> One possibility is that Dyfnwal was punished for harbouring insular Scandinavian potentates.<ref>[[#O2|Oram (2011)]] ch. 2.</ref> Whatever lay behind the campaign, it could have been utilised by the English [[Cerdicing dynasty]] as a way to overawe and intimidate neighbouring potentates.<ref>[[#M5|Molyneaux (2015)]] pp. 33, 77\u201378.</ref> M\u00e1el Coluim was probably a younger son of Dyfnwal, and not one of the sons mutilated by the English. The Gaelic name borne by M\u00e1el Coluim could indicate that he was born during a period of Scottish dominance over the Cumbrian realm, or that he was born during a time of relatively warm relations between the Scots and Cumbrians.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 5.</ref>\n\n==Rhydderch and conflict with the Scots==\n\n[[File:Rhydderch ap Dyfnwal (British Library MS Cotton Faustina B IX, folio 8v).jpg|alt=Refer to caption|right|thumb|The name of [[Rhydderch ap Dyfnwal]] as it appears on folio 8v of British Library Cotton Faustina B IX (the ''[[Chronicle of Melrose]]''): \"{{lang|la|Radhardus}}\".<ref>[[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 476; [[#S4|Stevenson, J (1835)]] p. 226; [[#C8|''Cotton MS Faustina B IX'' (n.d.)]].</ref>]]\n\nAfter the death of [[Illulb mac Custant\u00edn, King of Alba]] in 962, the Scottish kingship appears to have been taken up by [[Dub mac Ma\u00edl Choluim]], a man who was in turn replaced by Illulb's son, [[Cuil\u00e9n]].<ref>[[#B4|Broun (2004a)]].</ref> The latter's short reign appears to have been relatively uneventful.<ref>[[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 23.</ref> It nevertheless came to a violent end in 971, and there is reason to suspect that Cuil\u00e9n's killer was a son of Dyfnwal.<ref>[[#B1XXX|Broun (2015)]]; [[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 6; [[#C7|Clarkson (2012)]] ch. 9 \u00b6\u00b6 28\u201329; [[#O2|Oram (2011)]] chs. 2, 5; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 29; [[#BZZ1|Busse (2006b)]]; [[#B12|Busse (2006c)]]; [[#B11|Broun (2004c)]] p. 135 tab.; [[#M3|Macquarrie (2004)]]; [[#M2|Macquarrie (1998)]] pp. 6, 16; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] pp. 173 genealogy 6, 174 n. 10; [[#W2|Williams; Smyth; Kirby (1991)]] pp. 92, 104.</ref> The ninth- to twelfth-century ''[[Chronicle of the Kings of Alba]]'' reports that the killer was a certain [[Rhydderch ap Dyfnwal]], a man who slew Cuil\u00e9n for the sake of his own daughter.<ref>[[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 29; [[#M2|Macquarrie (1998)]] p. 16; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 476, 476 n. 1; [[#S3|Skene (1867)]] p. 151.</ref> The thirteenth-century ''Verse Chronicle'',<ref>[[#B1|Broun (2005)]] pp. 87\u201388 n. 37; [[#S3|Skene (1867)]] p. 179.</ref> the twelfth- to thirteenth-century ''[[Chronicle of Melrose]]'',<ref>[[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6\u00b6 32\u201333; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 204; [[#M3|Macquarrie (2004)]]; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] pp. 40\u201341; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 476; [[#S4|Stevenson, J (1835)]] p. 226.</ref> and the fourteenth-century ''[[Chronica gentis Scotorum]]'' likewise identify Cuil\u00e9n's killer as Rhydderch, the father of an abducted daughter raped by the Scottish king.<ref>[[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] pp. 93, 174 n. 10; [[#S2|Skene (1872)]] pp. 161\u2013162 bk 4 ch. 27; [[#S10|Skene (1871)]] pp. 169\u2013170 bk 4.</ref> Although there is no specific evidence that Rhydderch was himself a king,<ref>[[#M3|Macquarrie (2004)]]; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 67 n. 66.</ref> the fact that Cuil\u00e9n was involved with his daughter, coupled with the fact that his warband was evidently strong enough to overcome that of Cuil\u00e9n, suggests that Rhydderch must have been a man of eminent standing.<ref name=\"M3\">[[#M3|Macquarrie (2004)]].</ref>\n\n[[File:Cin\u00e1ed mac Ma\u00edl Choluim (Oxford Bodleian Library MS Rawlinson B 488, folio 15r).jpg|thumb|left|alt=Refer to caption|The name of [[Cin\u00e1ed mac Ma\u00edl Choluim]] as it appears on folio 15r of Oxford Bodleian Library Rawlinson B 488: \"{{lang|mga|Cinaeth mac Mail Cholaim}}\".<ref name=\"combine1\">[[#T3|''The Annals of Tigernach'' (2016)]] \u00a7 997.3; [[#A2|''Annals of Tigernach'' (2005)]] \u00a7 997.3; [[#B15|''Bodleian Library MS. Rawl. B. 488'' (n.d.)]].</ref>]]\n\nCuil\u00e9n seems to have been succeeded by his kinsman [[Cin\u00e1ed mac Ma\u00edl Choluim]].<ref>[[#B4|Broun (2004a)]]; [[#B7|Broun (2004b)]].</ref> One of the latter's first acts as [[King of Alba]] was evidently an invasion of the Kingdom of Strathclyde.<ref>[[#W10|Williams (2014)]]; [[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 25; [[#C7|Clarkson (2012)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 30; [[#O2|Oram (2011)]] ch. 5; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 35; [[#W4|Woolf (2009)]] p. 259; [[#B13|Busse (2006a)]]; [[#B7|Broun (2004b)]]; [[#H4|Hudson (1998)]] pp. 151, 161; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 512; [[#S3|Skene (1867)]] p. 10.</ref> This campaign could well have been a retaliatory response to Cuil\u00e9n's killing,<ref name=\"W14-425;W4-259\">[[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 25; [[#W4|Woolf (2009)]] p. 259.</ref> carried out in the context of crushing a British affront to Scottish authority.<ref>[[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 25.</ref> In any event, Cin\u00e1ed's invasion ended in defeat,<ref>[[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 35; [[#B7|Broun (2004b)]].</ref> a fact which coupled with Cuil\u00e9n's killing reveals that the Cumbrian realm was indeed a power to be reckoned with.<ref>[[#M4|McGuigan (2015)]] p. 140; [[#C7|Clarkson (2012)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 28; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 35.</ref> Whilst it is conceivable that Rhydderch could have succeeded Dyfnwal by the time of Cuil\u00e9n's fall,<ref>[[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 67 n. 66.</ref> another possibility is that Dyfnwal was still the king, and that Cin\u00e1ed's strike into Cumbrian territory was the last conflict of Dyfnwal's reign.<ref name=\"C3-935\">[[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 35.</ref> In fact, it could have been at about this point when M\u00e1el Coluim took up the kingship.<ref>[[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] p. 44 n. 107.</ref> According to the ''Chronicle of the Kings of Alba'', Cin\u00e1ed constructed some sort of fortification on the [[River Forth]], perhaps the strategically located Fords of Frew near [[Stirling]].<ref>[[#M4|McGuigan (2015)]] p. 149; [[#C7|Clarkson (2012)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 30; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 37; [[#B2|Broun (2007)]] p. 54; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] pp. 41\u201342; [[#D4|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 147\u2013148, 147 n. 167; [[#H4|Hudson (1998)]] pp. 151, 161; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 96; [[#B5|Breeze (1992)]]; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 512; [[#S3|Skene (1867)]] p. 10.</ref> One possibility is that this engineering project was undertaken in the context of limiting Cumbrian incursions.<ref>[[#C7|Clarkson (2012)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 30; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 37.</ref>\n\n==M\u00e1el Coluim and an assembly of kings==\n\n[[File:Dyfnwal ab Owain (Oxford Bodleian Library MS Jesus College 111, folio 59r).jpg|thumb|right|alt=Refer to caption|The name of [[Dyfnwal ab Owain]] as it appears on folio 59r of Oxford Jesus College 111 (the ''[[Red Book of Hergest]]''): \"{{lang|wlm|d\u1efdnwa\u1efba\u1efdn}}\".<ref>[[#R1|Rh\u0177s (1890)]] p. 262; [[#W7|Williams Ab Ithel (1860)]] pp. 26\u201327; [[#J5|''Jesus College MS. 111'' (n.d.)]]; [[#O5|''Oxford Jesus College MS. 111'' (n.d.)]].</ref>]]\n\nThere is evidence to suggest that both M\u00e1el Coluim<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 12; [[#E1|Edmonds (2014)]] p. 206; [[#W10|Williams (2014)]]; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] pp. 543\u2013544; [[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6\u00b6 30, 36; [[#C7|Clarkson (2012)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 29; [[#M10|Minard (2012)]]; [[#AX1|Aird (2009)]] p. 309; [[#BXX5|Breeze (2007)]] pp. 154\u2013155; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] p. 167; [[#M6|Minard (2006)]]; [[#M3|Macquarrie (2004)]]; [[#W11|Williams (2004)]]; [[#D4|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 142\u2013143; [[#D2|Duncan (2002)]] p. 23 n. 53; [[#J2|Jayakumar (2002)]] p. 34; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] pp. 66\u201367; [[#W5|Williams (1999)]] pp. 88, 116; [[#M2|Macquarrie (1998)]] p. 16; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 174 n. 9; [[#J1|Jennings (1994)]] p. 215; [[#W2|Williams; Smyth; Kirby (1991)]] pp. 104, 124; [[#S8|Stenton (1963)]] p. 324.</ref> and his father were amongst the assembled kings said to have [[King Edgar's council at Chester|convened with Edgar]] at [[Chester]] in 973.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 12; [[#E1|Edmonds (2014)]] p. 206; [[#W10|Williams (2014)]]; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] pp. 543\u2013544; [[#C7|Clarkson (2012)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 29; [[#O2|Oram (2011)]] ch. 2; [[#W4|Woolf (2009)]] p. 259; [[#BXX5|Breeze (2007)]] pp. 154\u2013155; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] pp. 124, 167; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 208; [[#M3|Macquarrie (2004)]]; [[#W11|Williams (2004)]]; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] p. 42; [[#D4|Davidson (2002)]] p. 143; [[#J2|Jayakumar (2002)]] p. 34; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] pp. 54\u201355, 67; [[#M2|Macquarrie (1998)]] p. 16; [[#W2|Williams; Smyth; Kirby (1991)]] pp. 104, 124; [[#S8|Stenton (1963)]] p. 324.</ref> According to the \"D\", \"[[Peterborough Chronicle|E]]\", and \"F\" versions of the ''Anglo-Saxon Chronicle'', after having been consecrated king that year, this English monarch assembled a massive naval force and met with six kings at Chester.<ref>[[#F5|Firth (2018)]] p. 48; [[#H10|Holland (2016)]] ch. Malmesbury \u00b6 6; [[#M4|McGuigan (2015)]] pp. 143\u2013144, 144 n. 466; [[#M5|Molyneaux (2015)]] p. 34; [[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6\u00b6 9\u201310, 7 n. 11; [[#W10|Williams (2014)]]; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] pp. 543\u2013544; [[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 30; [[#M7|Molyneaux (2011)]] pp. 66, 69, 88; [[#BXX5|Breeze (2007)]] p. 153; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] p. 124; [[#M9|Matthews (2007)]] p. 10; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] pp. 207\u2013208; [[#F4|Forte; Oram; Pedersen (2005)]] p. 218; [[#IX1|Irvine (2004)]] p. 59; [[#K3|Karkov (2004)]] p. 108; [[#W11|Williams (2004)]]; [[#D4|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 138, 140, 140 n. 140, 144; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 50; [[#XB103|Baker (2000)]] pp. 83\u201384; [[#W5|Williams (1999)]] pp. 88, 116, 191 n. 50; [[#W9|Whitelock (1996)]] pp. 229\u2013230; [[#2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 97; [[#S8|Stenton (1963)]] p. 364; [[#A5|Anderson, AO (1908)]] pp. 75\u201376; [[#S12|Stevenson, WH (1898)]]; [[#T6|Thorpe (1861)]] pp. 225\u2013227.</ref> By the tenth century, the number of kings who met with him was alleged to have been eight, as evidenced by the tenth-century ''Life of St Swithun''.<ref>[[#E2|Edmonds (2015)]] p. 61 n. 94; [[#K2|Keynes (2015)]] pp. 113\u2013114; [[#M4|McGuigan (2015)]] pp. 143\u2013144; [[#E1|Edmonds (2014)]] p. 206, 206 n. 60; [[#W10|Williams (2014)]]; [[#M7|Molyneaux (2011)]] p. 67; [[#BXX5|Breeze (2007)]] p. 154; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] p. 124; [[#M9|Matthews (2007)]] p. 10; [[#K3|Karkov (2004)]] p. 108; [[#W11|Williams (2004)]]; [[#D4|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 140\u2013141, 141 n. 145, 145; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 51; [[#W5|Williams (1999)]] pp. 191 n. 50, 203 n. 71; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] pp. 97\u201398; [[#J1|Jennings (1994)]] pp. 213\u2013214; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 479 n. 1; [[#S12|Stevenson, WH (1898)]]; [[#SA1|Skeat (1881)]] pp. 468\u2013469.</ref> By the twelfth century, the eight kings began to be named and were alleged to have rowed Edgar down the [[River Dee, Cumbria|River Dee]], as evidenced by sources such as the twelfth-century texts ''[[Chronicon ex chronicis]]'',<ref>[[#F5|Firth (2018)]] p. 48; [[#E2|Edmonds (2015)]] p. 61 n. 94; [[#M4|McGuigan (2015)]] pp. 143\u2013144, n. 466; [[#K2|Keynes (2015)]] p. 114; [[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6\u00b6 12\u201314; [[#E1|Edmonds (2014)]] p. 206; [[#W10|Williams (2014)]]; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] pp. 543\u2013544; [[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 30; [[#M7|Molyneaux (2011)]] pp. 66\u201367; [[#BXX5|Breeze (2007)]] p. 153; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] p. 124; [[#M9|Matthews (2007)]] p. 11; [[#F4|Forte; Oram; Pedersen (2005)]] p. 218; [[#K3|Karkov (2004)]] p. 108; [[#W11|Williams (2004)]]; [[#D4|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 13, 134, 134 n. 111, 142, 145; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] pp. 57\u201358; [[#W5|Williams (1999)]] pp. 116, 191 n. 50; [[#W9|Whitelock (1996)]] p. 230 n. 1; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 97; [[#J1|Jennings (1994)]] p. 213; [[#S9|Smyth (1989)]] pp. 226\u2013227; [[#S8|Stenton (1963)]] p. 364; [[#A5|Anderson, AO (1908)]] pp. 76\u201377; [[#S12|Stevenson, WH (1898)]]; [[#F1|Forester (1854)]] pp. 104\u2013105; [[#SA2|Stevenson, J (1853)]] pp. 247\u2013248; [[#T7|Thorpe (1848)]] pp. 142\u2013143.</ref> ''[[Gesta regum Anglorum]]'',<ref>[[#E2|Edmonds (2015)]] p. 61 n. 94; [[#K2|Keynes (2015)]] p. 114; [[#M4|McGuigan (2015)]] p. 144, n. 466; [[#E1|Edmonds (2014)]] p. 206; [[#W10|Williams (2014)]]; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] pp. 543\u2013544; [[#M7|Molyneaux (2011)]] pp. 66\u201367; [[#BXX5|Breeze (2007)]] p. 153; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] p. 124; [[#M9|Matthews (2007)]] pp. 10\u201311; [[#K3|Karkov (2004)]] p. 108, 108 n. 123; [[#W11|Williams (2004)]]; [[#D4|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 143, 145; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] pp. 59\u201360; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 97; [[#A5|Anderson, AO (1908)]] p. 77 n. 1; [[#S12|Stevenson, WH (1898)]]; [[#G4|Giles (1847)]] p. 147 bk. 2 ch. 8; [[#H7|Hardy (1840)]] p. 236 bk. 2 ch. 148.</ref> and ''[[De primo Saxonum adventu]]'',<ref>[[#M4|McGuigan (2015)]] p. 144, 144 n. 469; [[#D4|Davidson (2002)]] p. 142, 142 n. 149, 145; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] pp. 60\u201361; [[#A5|Anderson, AO (1908)]] p. 76 n. 2; [[#AA2|Arnold (1885)]] p. 372.</ref> as well as the thirteenth-century ''[[Chronica majora]]'',<ref>[[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 60; [[#LA1|Luard (1872)]] pp. 466\u2013467.</ref> and both the Wendover<ref>[[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 60; [[#G3|Giles (1849)]] pp. 263\u2013264; [[#C5|Coxe (1841)]] p. 415.</ref> and Paris versions of ''Flores historiarum''.<ref>[[#L1|Luard (2012)]] p. 513; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 60; [[#Y1|Yonge (1853)]] p. 484.</ref>{{#tag:ref|Another source linking Dyfnwal and M\u00e1el Coluim to the assembly is the ''Chronicle of Melrose''.<ref>[[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] p. 42; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] pp. 478\u2013479; [[#S1|Stevenson, J (1856)]] p. 100; [[#S4|Stevenson, J (1835)]] p. 34.</ref> If it was not Dyfnwal who attended the assembly, another possibility is that the like-named attendee was [[Domnall ua N\u00e9ill, King of Tara]].<ref>[[#D4|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 146\u2013147.</ref>|group=note}}\n\n[[File:Edgar, King of the English, rowed on the River Dee.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Black and white illustration of a king being rowed down a river in a rowboat by eight other kings|An early twentieth-century depiction of Edgar being rowed down the [[River Dee, Cumbria|River Dee]] by eight kings.<ref>[[#C2|''Cassell's History of England'' (1909)]] p. 53.</ref> According to the ''Anglo-Saxon Chronicle'', Edgar met six kings at Chester. By the twelfth century, chroniclers alleged that eight kings rowed Edgar down the river in an act of submission.<ref>[[#W11|Williams (2004)]].</ref> One of these eight was M\u00e1el Coluim himself.]]\n\nWhilst the symbolic tale of the men rowing Edgar down the river may be an unhistorical embellishment, most of the names accorded to the eight kings can be associated with contemporary rulers, suggesting that some of these men may have taken part in a concord with him.<ref>[[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 74.</ref>{{#tag:ref|Two of the kings are accorded names are of uncertain meaning.<ref>[[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] pp. 67\u201374.</ref>|group=note}} Although the latter accounts allege that the kings submitted to Edgar, the ''Anglo-Saxon Chronicle'' merely states that they came to an agreement of cooperation with him, and thus became his {{lang|ang|efen-wyrhtan}} (\"co-workers\", \"even-workers\", \"fellow-workers\").<ref>[[#D4|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 66\u201367, 140; [[#D1|Davidson (2001)]] p. 208; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] pp. 77\u201378.</ref> One possibility is that the assembly somehow relates to Edmund's attested incursion into Cumbria in 945. According to the same source, when Edmund {{lang|ang|let}} Cumbria to M\u00e1el Coluim mac Domnaill, he had done so on the condition that the latter would be his {{lang|ang|mid-wyrhta}} (\"co-worker\", \"even-worker\", \"fellow-worker\", \"together-wright\").<ref>[[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] p. 16 n. 35; [[#D4|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 115\u2013116, 140; [[#D1|Davidson (2001)]] p. 208; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] pp. 77\u201378; [[#W9|Whitelock (1996)]] p. 224; [[#A5|Anderson, AO (1908)]] p. 74; [[#T6|Thorpe (1861)]] pp. 212\u2013213.</ref> Less reliable non-contemporary sources such as ''De primo Saxonum adventu'',<ref>[[#KB1|Keynes (2008)]] p. 51; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 211; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] pp. 65\u201366; [[#A6|Anderson, MO (1960)]] p. 104; [[#A5|Anderson, AO (1908)]] p. 77; [[#AA2|Arnold (1885)]] p. 382.</ref> both the Wendover<ref>[[#A6|Anderson, MO (1960)]] p. 107, 107 n. 1; [[#G3|Giles (1849)]] p. 264; [[#C5|Coxe (1841)]] p. 416.</ref> and Paris versions of ''Flores historiarum'',<ref>[[#L1|Luard (2012)]] p. 513; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] pp. 65\u201366; [[#A6|Anderson, MO (1960)]] p. 107, 107 n. 1; [[#Y1|Yonge (1853)]] p. 485.</ref> and ''Chronica majora'' allege that Edgar granted [[Lothian]] to Cin\u00e1ed in 975.<ref>[[#A6|Anderson, MO (1960)]] p. 107, 107 nn. 1, 4; [[#A5|Anderson, AO (1908)]] pp. 77\u201378 n. 6; [[#LA1|Luard (1872)]] pp. 467\u2013468.</ref> If this supposed grant formed a part of the episode at Chester, it along with the concord of 945 could indicate that the assembly of 975 was not a submission as such, but more of a conference concerning mutual cooperation along the English borderlands.<ref>[[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] p. 125; [[#W11|Williams (2004)]]; [[#D4|Davidson (2002)]] p. 5; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] pp. 78\u201379.</ref> Although the precise chronology of Cumbrian expansion is uncertain, by 927 the southern frontier of the Kingdom of Strathclyde appears to have reached the [[River Eamont]], close to [[Penrith, Cumbria|Penrith]].<ref>[[#D6|Dumville (2018)]] pp. 72, 110, 118; [[#E2|Edmonds (2015)]] pp. 44, 53; [[#C1|Charles-Edwards (2013a)]] p. 20; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] pp. 9, 481; [[#P1|Parsons (2011)]] p. 138 n. 62; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 10; [[#D5|Davies (2009)]] p. 73, 73 n. 40; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] p. 165; [[#C11|Clancy (2006)]]; [[#T4|Todd (2005)]] p. 96; [[#S8|Stenton (1963)]] p. 328.</ref> As such, the location of the assembly of 973 at Chester would have been a logical site for all parties.<ref>[[#B9|Barrow (2001)]] p. 89.</ref>{{#tag:ref|At about the same time as the assembly, ''De primo Saxonum adventu'' also notes that Edgar partitioned the Northumbrian ealdormanry into northern and southern divisions, split between the [[Tees]] and {{lang|la|Myreforth}}. If the latter location refers to the [[mud flats]] between the [[River Esk, Cumbria|River Esk]] and the Solway Firth,<ref>[[#M4|McGuigan (2015)]] p. 147; [[#AX1|Aird (2009)]] p. 309; [[#D4|Davidson (2002)]] p. 149, 149 n. 172; [[#D2|Duncan (2002)]] p. 24; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 140; [[#A5|Anderson, AO (1908)]] p. 77; [[#AA2|Arnold (1885)]] p. 382.</ref> it would reveal that what is today [[Cumberland]] had fallen outwith Cumbrian royal authority and into the hands of the English.<ref>[[#D2|Duncan (2002)]] pp. 24\u201325.</ref>|group=note}}\n\n[[File:Edgar (British Library Cotton MS Tiberius B I, folio 142v).jpg|alt=Refer to caption|right|thumb|The name of Edgar as it appears on folio 142v of British Library Cotton Tiberius B I (the \"C\" version of the ''Anglo-Saxon Chronicle''): \"{{lang|ang|Eadgar Angla cing}}\".<ref>[[#O1|O'Keeffe (2001)]] p. 81; [[#W9|Whitelock (1996)]] p. 230; [[#T6|Thorpe (1861)]] p. 226; [[#C6|''Cotton MS Tiberius B I'' (n.d.)]].</ref>]]\n\nOne of the other named kings was Cin\u00e1ed.<ref>[[#AX1|Aird (2009)]] p. 309; [[#W4|Woolf (2009)]] p. 259; [[#BXX5|Breeze (2007)]] p. 155; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] p. 124; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 208; [[#B7|Broun (2004b)]]; [[#D4|Davidson (2002)]] p. 142.</ref> Considering the fact that the ''Anglo-Saxon Chronicle'' numbers the kings at six, if Cin\u00e1ed was indeed present, it is unlikely that his rival, Cuil\u00e9n's brother [[Amla\u00edb, King of Scotland|Amla\u00edb mac Illuilb]], was also in attendance.<ref name=\"W1-208\">[[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 208.</ref> Although the chronology concerning the reigns of Cin\u00e1ed and Amla\u00edb mac Illuilb is uncertain<ref>[[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] pp. 208\u2013209.</ref>\u2014with Amla\u00edb mac Illuilb perhaps reigning from 971/976\u2013977<ref>[[#D2|Duncan (2002)]] pp. 21\u201322; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 93.</ref> and Cin\u00e1ed from 971/977\u2013995<ref name=\"W1-208\"/>\u2014the part played by the King of Alba at the assembly could well have concerned the frontier of his realm.<ref name=\"M9-25\">[[#M9|Matthews (2007)]] p. 25.</ref> One of the other named kings seems to have been [[Maccus mac Arailt]],<ref>[[#J3|Jennings (2015)]]; [[#W15|Wadden (2015)]] pp. 27\u201328; [[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 12; [[#W10|Williams (2014)]]; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] p. 543; [[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 31; [[#W4|Woolf (2009)]] p. 259; [[#BXX5|Breeze (2007)]] p. 155; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] pp. 124\u2013125, 167, 222; [[#M9|Matthews (2007)]] p. 25; [[#F4|Forte; Oram; Pedersen (2005)]] p. 218; [[#D4|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 143, 146, 151; [[#J2|Jayakumar (2002)]] p. 34; [[#W5|Williams (1999)]] p. 116; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 97; [[#J1|Jennings (1994)]] pp. 213\u2013214; [[#S8|Stenton (1963)]] p. 364.</ref> whilst another could have been this man's brother, [[Gofraid mac Arailt|Gofraid]].<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 12; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] p. 544; [[#BXX5|Breeze (2007)]] p. 156; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] pp. 125 n. 10, 222; [[#M9|Matthews (2007)]] p. 25; [[#D4|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 143, 146, 151; [[#J2|Jayakumar (2002)]] p. 34.</ref> These two [[Kingdom of the Isles|Islesmen]] may have been regarded a threats by the Scots<ref name=\"M9-25\"/> and Cumbrians.<ref name=\"W1-208\"/> Maccus and Gofraid are recorded to have devastated [[Anglesey]] at the beginning of the decade,<ref>[[#G1|Gough-Cooper (2015b)]] p. 43 \u00a7 b993.1; [[#W10|Williams (2014)]]; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] p. 192; [[#M9|Matthews (2007)]] pp. 9, 25; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] pp. 206\u2013207; [[#D4|Davidson (2002)]] p. 151; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] pp. 478\u2013479 n. 6; [[#R1|Rh\u0177s (1890)]] p. 262; [[#W7|Williams Ab Ithel (1860)]] pp. 24\u201325.</ref> which could indicate that Edgar's assembly was undertaken as a means to counter the menace posed by these energetic insular Scandinavians.<ref>[[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] p. 545; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] pp. 222\u2013223; [[#M9|Matthews (2007)]] pp. 9, 15; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] pp. 207\u2013208.</ref> In fact, there is evidence to suggest that, as a consequence of the assembly at Chester, the brothers may have turned their attention from the [[Great Britain|British mainland]] westwards towards [[Ireland]].<ref>[[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] pp. 126\u2013127, 222\u2013223; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 208.</ref>\n\n[[File:Thored Gunnerson (British Library Cotton MS Domitian A VIII, folio 58v).jpg|left|thumb|alt=Refer to caption|The name of [[Thored Gunnerson]] as it appears on folio 58v of British Library Cotton Domitian A VIII (the \"F\" version of the ''Anglo-Saxon Chronicle''): \"{{lang|la|Thored filius Gunnerses}}\".<ref>[[#XB103|Baker (2000)]] p. 83; [[#C13|''Cotton MS Domitian A VIII'' (n.d.)]].</ref>]]\n\nAnother aspect of the assembly may have concerned the remarkable rising power of [[Amla\u00edb C\u00faar\u00e1n]] in Ireland.<ref>[[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] p. 545; [[#D4|Davidson (2002)]] p. 147.</ref> Edgar may have wished to not only reign in men such as Maccus and Gofraid, but prevent them\u2014and the Scots and Cumbrians\u2014from affiliating themselves with Amla\u00edb C\u00faar\u00e1n, and recognising the latter's authority in the Irish Sea region.<ref>[[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] p. 545.</ref> Another factor concerning Edgar, and his Scottish and Cumbrian counterparts, may have been the stability of the northern English frontier. For example, a certain [[Thored Gunnerson]] is recorded to have ravaged [[Westmorland]] in 966, an action that may have been undertaken by the English in the context of a response to Cumbrian southward expansion.<ref>[[#W10|Williams (2014)]]; [[#W11|Williams (2004)]]; [[#W9|Whitelock (1996)]] p. 229; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 472; [[#T6|Thorpe (1861)]] p. 223.</ref>{{#tag:ref|According to the ''Life of St Cathr\u00f3e'', after Dyfnwal escorted Cathr\u00f3e to the frontier of his realm, the latter was then escorted by a certain Gunderic to the domain of Erich at York.<ref>[[#M4|McGuigan (2015)]] p. 98; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 441; [[#S3|Skene (1867)]] p. 116; [[#C4|Colganvm (1645)]] p. 497.</ref> It is possible that Gunderico is identical to Thored's father, and identical to the Gunner who appears is charter evidence from 931\u2013963.<ref>[[#M4|McGuigan (2015)]] pp. 98\u201399.</ref>|group=note}} Although the Scottish invasion of Cumbrian and English territory unleashed after Cin\u00e1ed's inauguration could have been intended to tackle Cumbrian opposition,<ref name=\"W14-425;W4-259\"/> another possibility is that the campaign could have been executed as a way to counter any occupation of Cumbrian territories by Thored.<ref>[[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 26.</ref>\n\n==M\u00e1el Coluim's reign and death==\n\n[[File:M\u00e1el Coluim mac Domnaill (Oxford Bodleian Library MS Rawlinson B 488, folio 15v) 2.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Refer to caption|M\u00e1el Coluim's title as it appears on folio 15v of Oxford Bodleian Library Rawlinson B 488: \"{{lang|mga|r\u00ed Bretan Tuaisceirt}}\" (\"king of the Britons of the north\").<ref name=\"combine1\"/>]]\n\nBoth Dyfnwal<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 17; [[#W10|Williams (2014)]]; [[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6\u00b6 30, 36; [[#M10|Minard (2012)]]; [[#O2|Oram (2011)]] ch. 2; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 41; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 184; [[#B12|Busse (2006c)]]; [[#M6|Minard (2006)]]; [[#B11|Broun (2004c)]] pp. 128\u2013129; [[#M3|Macquarrie (2004)]]; [[#D4|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 39, 146; [[#M2|Macquarrie (1998)]] pp. 15\u201316; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] pp. 101, 174 n. 8; [[#W2|Williams; Smyth; Kirby (1991)]] p. 104.</ref> and Edgar died in 975.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 17; [[#W10|Williams (2014)]]; [[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 35; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 41; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 208; [[#W2|Williams; Smyth; Kirby (1991)]] p. 124.</ref> According to various [[Irish annals]], Dyfnwal met his end whilst undertaking a pilgrimage.<ref>[[#T2|''The Annals of Ulster'' (2017)]] \u00a7 975.2; [[#T3|''The Annals of Tigernach'' (2016)]] \u00a7 975.3; [[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 17, 7 n. 19; [[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 36; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 41; [[#T1|''The Annals of Ulster'' (2008)]] \u00a7 975.2; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 184; [[#A2|''Annals of Tigernach'' (2005)]] \u00a7 975.3; [[#B11|Broun (2004c)]] pp. 128\u2013129; [[#M3|Macquarrie (2004)]]; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] p. 42; [[#D4|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 39, 146; [[#M2|Macquarrie (1998)]] pp. 15\u201316; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 174 n. 8; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 480, 480 n. 7.</ref> Surviving sources fail to note the Cumbrian realm between the obituaries of Dyfnwal in 975 and M\u00e1el Coluim in 997.<ref>[[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 41.</ref> Quite when Dyfnwal ceased to possess the kingship is uncertain. On one hand, there is reason to suspect that Rhydderch possessed power in 971.<ref name=\"M3\"/> On the other hand, it is also possible that Dyfnwal was still reigning in 973.<ref>[[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 30; [[#B12|Busse (2006c)]]; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 55.</ref> In fact, this could have been the point when he ceded power to M\u00e1el Coluim: conceivably as a consequence of Rhydderch's assassination of Cuil\u00e9n two years beforehand.<ref>[[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 36; [[#O2|Oram (2011)]] ch. 2.</ref> Alternately, Dyfnwal may have retained royal control until setting off upon his pilgrimage.<ref>[[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 30; [[#B12|Busse (2006c)]]; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 101; [[#S8|Stenton (1963)]] p. 364.</ref> If correct, it could have been Edgar's death that precipitated this final trek, and the transference of the Cumbrian kingship to M\u00e1el Coluim.<ref name=\"W1-208\"/>{{#tag:ref|In fact, the upheaval caused by the absence of Dyfnwal and Edgar could well have contributed to Cin\u00e1ed's final elimination of Amla\u00edb mac Illuilb in 997.<ref name=\"W1-208\"/>|group=note}}\n\n[[File:M\u00e1el Coluim mac Domnaill (British Library MS Cotton Faustina B IX, folio 9r).jpg|alt=Refer to caption|left|thumb|[[M\u00e1el Coluim I of Strathclyde|M\u00e1el Coluim]]'s title as it appears on folio 9r of British Library Cotton Faustina B IX: \"{{lang|la|rex Cumbrorum}}\".<ref>[[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 478; [[#S1|Stevenson, J (1856)]] p. 100; [[#S4|Stevenson, J (1835)]] p. 34; [[#C8|''Cotton MS Faustina B IX'' (n.d.)]].</ref>{{#tag:ref|Only three rulers of the Kingdom of Strathclyde were styled King of the Cumbrians: M\u00e1el Coluim himself, M\u00e1el Coluim's father, and M\u00e1el Coluim's grandfather, [[Owain ap Dyfnwal (fl. 934)|Owain ap Dyfnwal]].<ref>[[#M10|Minard (2012)]]; [[#M6|Minard (2006)]].</ref>|group=note}}]]\n\nM\u00e1el Coluim's part in the assembly could have partly concerned his father's impending pilgrimage, and that he sought surety for Dyfnwal's safe passage through Edgar's realm.<ref name=\"M9-25\"/> The fact that M\u00e1el Coluim is identified as one of the assembled kings could indicate that Dyfnwal had relinquished control to him at some point before the convention.<ref>[[#W10|Williams (2014)]]; [[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 30; [[#C7|Clarkson (2012)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 29; [[#M3|Macquarrie (2004)]]; [[#D4|Davidson (2002)]] p. 146; [[#W2|Williams; Smyth; Kirby (1991)]] p. 104.</ref> Conversely, M\u00e1el Coluim's title could instead indicate that he merely represented his aged father,<ref>[[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 30.</ref> and acted as regent.<ref>[[#BXX5|Breeze (2007)]] p. 154.</ref> Evidence that M\u00e1el Coluim had indeed assumed the kingship before the assembly may exist in the record of a certain {{lang|la|Malcolm dux}} who witnessed an [[Anglo-Saxon charters|English royal charter]] in 970 at [[Woolmer]].<ref>[[#M4|McGuigan (2015)]] p. 101, 101 n. 302; [[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 5, 7 n. 3; [[#BXX4|Birch (1893)]] pp. 557\u2013560 \u00a7 1266; [[#T1001|Thorpe (1865)]] pp. 237\u2013243; [[#M1|''Malcolm 4'' (n.d.)]]; [[#S7|''S 779'' (n.d.)]].</ref> Although the authenticity of this document is questionable, the attested Malcolm could well be identical to M\u00e1el Coluim himself.<ref>[[#M5|Molyneaux (2015)]] p. 57 n. 45; [[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 5; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] p. 544; [[#M7|Molyneaux (2011)]] p. 66; [[#KB1|Keynes (2008)]] p. 50 n. 232; [[#D4|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 147, 147 n. 166, 152; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 71; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 174 n. 9; [[#M1|''Malcolm 4'' (n.d.)]].</ref>{{#tag:ref|This charter is composed of Latin and Old English text. The document may be evidence of Scottish and Cumbrian submission to the English. For example, one place the text reads in Latin: \"I, Edgar, ruler of the beloved island of Albion, subjected to us of the rule of the Scots and Cumbrians and the Britons and of all regions round about ...\". The corresponding Old English text reads: \"I, Edgar, exalted as king over the English people by His [God's] grace, and He has now subjected to my authority the Scots and Cumbrians and also the Britons and all that this island has inside ...\".<ref>[[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 52, 52 n. 6; [[#BXX4|Birch (1893)]] pp. 557\u2013560 \u00a7 1266; [[#T1001|Thorpe (1865)]] pp. 237\u2013243; [[#S7|''S 779'' (n.d.)]].</ref>|group=note}} If M\u00e1el Coluim was indeed king in 973, Dyfnwal's role at the assembly may have been that of an '[[Diplomat|elder statesman]]' of sorts\u2014possibly serving as an adviser or mentor\u2014especially considering his decades of experience in international affairs.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 12; [[#C7|Clarkson (2012)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 29; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 35.</ref>{{#tag:ref|If M\u00e1el Coluim was indeed king, the attestation of {{lang|la|Malcolm dux}} would be the only record of a foreign king witnessing one of Edgar's charters.<ref>[[#D4|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 147, 152.</ref>|group=note}}\n\n{{Quote box\n |quote  = And Mael Coluim, with hundreds of deeds, before the hands of the land of the Britons, with the bright hospitality of every good battle, the good son of Domnall, son of Eogan.\n |source = \u2014 excerpt from ''[[Saltair na Rann]]'' praising M\u00e1el Coluim, and proclaiming his descent from [[Dyfnwal ab Owain]] and [[Owain ap Dyfnwal (fl. 934)|Owain ap Dyfnwal]].<ref>[[#S5|''Saltair na Rann'' (2011)]] \u00a7\u00a7 2373\u20132376; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] pp. 101, 174 nn. 8\u20139; [[#M1002|Mac Eoin (1961)]] pp. 53 \u00a7\u00a7 2373\u20132376, 55\u201356; [[#S6|''Saltair na Rann'' (n.d.)]] \u00a7\u00a7 2373\u20132376.</ref>\n |align  = right\n |width  = 40%\n |quoted = 1\n |bgcolor= cornsilk\n}}\n\nIf M\u00e1el Coluim succeeded Dyfnwal, it could mean that Rhydderch\u2014if he was indeed M\u00e1el Coluim's brother\u2014was either dead or unable to reign as king. Whilst it is possible that the sons of Dyfnwal maimed by the English in 945 were still alive in the 970s,<ref name=\"C3-935\"/> the horrific injuries endured by these men would have meant that they were deemed unfit to rule.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 5; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 35.</ref> Notwithstanding the uncertainties surrounding his accession, M\u00e1el Coluim's reign was evidently unremarkable.<ref>[[#B12|Busse (2006c)]].</ref> Certainly, no source records Scottish-Cumbrian political relations at about the inception of M\u00e1el Coluim's reign,<ref>[[#C7|Clarkson (2012)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 29.</ref> although the fact that Dyfnwal left for Rome could be evidence that the latter did not regard the realm or dynasty to be threatened during his absence.<ref>[[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] p. 42.</ref> \n\nM\u00e1el Coluim\u2014alongside contemporary Irish, English, and [[King of the Franks|Frankish]] kings\u2014is commemorated by several lines of panegyric verse preserved by the tenth-century ''[[Saltair na Rann]]''.<ref>[[#M4|McGuigan (2015)]] p. 140; [[#S5|''Saltair na Rann'' (2011)]] \u00a7\u00a7 2373\u20132376; [[#H9|Hudson (2002)]] pp. 34, 36; [[#H5|Hudson (1996)]] p. 102; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] pp. 101, 174 nn. 8\u20139; [[#H1|Hudson (1991)]] p. 147; [[#M1002|Mac Eoin (1961)]] pp. 53 \u00a7\u00a7 2373\u20132376, 55\u201356; [[#S6|''Saltair na Rann'' (n.d.)]] \u00a7\u00a7 2373\u20132376.</ref> He died in 997, the same year as his northern counterpart, [[Custant\u00edn mac Cuil\u00e9in, King of Alba]].<ref>[[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 222.</ref> M\u00e1el Coluim's demise is recorded by the ''Annals of Clonmacnoise'',<ref>[[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] p. 31; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 66; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 174 n. 9; [[#M1002|Mac Eoin (1961)]] p. 56; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 517 n. 5; [[#M1001|Murphy (1896)]] p. 163.</ref> the ''Annals of Ulster'',<ref>[[#T2|''The Annals of Ulster'' (2017)]] \u00a7 997.5; [[#T1|''The Annals of Ulster'' (2008)]] \u00a7 997.5; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 184, 184 n. 17; [[#D4|Davidson (2002)]] p. 39; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 66; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 174 n. 9; [[#M1002|Mac Eoin (1961)]] p. 56; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 517 n. 5.</ref> ''Chronicon Scotorum'',<ref>[[#C1003|''Chronicon Scotorum'' (2012)]] \u00a7 997; [[#C1002|''Chronicon Scotorum'' (2010)]] \u00a7 997; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 66; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 174 n. 9; [[#M1002|Mac Eoin (1961)]] p. 56; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 517 n. 5.</ref> and the ''Annals of Tigernach''. The latter styles him \"king of the north Britons\".<ref>[[#T3|''The Annals of Tigernach'' (2016)]] \u00a7 997.3; [[#A2|''Annals of Tigernach'' (2005)]] \u00a7 997.3; [[#M3|Macquarrie (2004)]]; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] p. 31; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 66; [[#M2|Macquarrie (1998)]] p. 16; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 174 n. 9; [[#M1002|Mac Eoin (1961)]] p. 56; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 517.</ref> M\u00e1el Coluim seems to have been succeeded by a brother, [[Owain ap Dyfnwal (died 1015)|Owain]].<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 17; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 41; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] pp. 222, 233, 236.</ref> The latter appears to have been succeeded by [[Owain Foel]],<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 47.</ref> a man who may well have been a son of M\u00e1el Coluim.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] chs. genealogical tables, 8 \u00b6 7; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] p. 572 fig. 17.4; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] pp. 236, 238 tab. 6.4; [[#B11|Broun (2004c)]] pp. 128 n. 66, 135 tab.; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] p. 44, 44 n. 107; [[#D2|Duncan (2002)]] pp. 29, 41.</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==Citations==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==References==\n\n===Primary sources===\n{{refbegin|colwidth=30em}}\n*{{cite book |year=1908 |editor1-l