{"title_page": "Dyfnwal ab Owain", "text_new": "{{Infobox royalty\n| name         = Dyfnwal ab Owain\n| title        = [[King of Strathclyde]]\n| image        = Dyfnwal ab Owain (Oxford Bodleian Library MS Rawlinson B 488, folio 15r).jpg\n| alt          = Refer to caption\n| caption      = Dyfnwal's name as it appears on folio 15r of Oxford Bodleian Library Rawlinson B 488 (the ''[[Annals of Tigernach]]''): \"{{lang|mga|Domnall mac Eoain}}\".<ref>[[#T3|''The Annals of Tigernach'' (2016)]] \u00a7 975.3; [[#A2|''Annals of Tigernach'' (2005)]] \u00a7 975.3; [[#B15|''Bodleian Library MS. Rawl. B. 488'' (n.d.)]].</ref>{{#tag:ref|The [[Welsh language|Welsh]] personal name ''Dyfnwal'' is a [[cognate]] of the [[Gaelic languages|Gaelic]] ''Domnall''.<ref>[[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] pp. xiii, 184, 184 n. 17; [[#K1|Koch (2006)]]; [[#B3|Bruford (2000)]] pp. 64, 65 n. 76; [[#S16|Schrijver (1995)]] p. 81.</ref>|group=note}}\n| predecessor  = [[Owain ap Dyfnwal (fl. 934)|Owain ap Dyfnwal]]\n| successor    = [[Rhydderch ap Dyfnwal|Rhydderch]] or [[M\u00e1el Coluim, King of Strathclyde|M\u00e1el Coluim]]\n| death_date   = 975\n| issue        = Rhydderch?, M\u00e1el Coluim, and [[Owain ap Dyfnwal (died 1015)|Owain]]?\n| father       = Owain ap Dyfnwal\n}}\n\n'''Dyfnwal ab Owain''' (died 975) was a tenth-century [[King of Strathclyde]].{{#tag:ref|Since the 2000s academics have accorded Dyfnwal various [[patronym]]s in English secondary sources: ''Domnall mac Eogain'',<ref>[[#B12|Busse (2006c)]].</ref> ''Dunmail map Owain'',<ref>[[#S11|Snyder (2003)]].</ref> ''Dwnwallon ab Owain'',<ref name=\"C10\">[[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]].</ref> ''Dyfnwal ab Owain'',<ref>[[#M10|Minard (2012)]]; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]]; [[#BXX5|Breeze (2007)]]; [[#B12|Busse (2006c)]]; [[#M6|Minard (2006)]]; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]].</ref> and ''Dyfnwal map Ywain''.<ref name=\"M1\">[[#M1|Macquarrie (2004a)]].</ref> Likewise, since the 1990s academics have accorded Dyfnwal various personal names in English secondary sources: ''Domnaldus'',<ref>[[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]]; [[#D3|Downham (2003)]].</ref> ''Domnall'',<ref>[[#BZZ1|Busse (2006b)]]; [[#B12|Busse (2006c)]].</ref> ''Donald'',<ref>[[#K2|Keynes (2015)]]; [[#M4|McGuigan (2015b)]]; [[#W10|Williams (2014)]]; [[#W14|Walker (2013)]]; [[#M10|Minard (2012)]]; [[#BXX5|Breeze (2007)]]; [[#M6|Minard (2006)]]; [[#B4|Broun (2004a)]]; [[#M3|Macquarrie (2004b)]]; [[#D2|Duncan (2002)]]; [[#W16|Williams; Smyth; Kirby (1991)]]; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]].</ref> ''Dovenald'',<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]].</ref> ''Dufnal'',<ref>[[#M10|Minard (2012)]]; [[#M6|Minard (2006)]]; [[#J2|Jayakumar (2002)]]; [[#W16|Williams; Smyth; Kirby (1991)]].</ref> ''Dumnagual'',<ref>[[#D2|Duncan (2002)]].</ref> ''Dunguallon'',<ref>[[#H3|Hicks (2003)]]; [[#D2|Duncan (2002)]].</ref> ''Dunmail'',<ref>[[#C1|Cannon (2015)]]; [[#W13|Williams (2004c)]]; [[#BXX5|Breeze (2007)]]; [[#S11|Snyder (2003)]].</ref> ''Dunwallon'',<ref>[[#M9|Matthews (2007)]].</ref> ''Dyfnal'',<ref>[[#BXX5|Breeze (2007)]]; [[#H5|Hudson (1996)]]; [[#H12|Hudson (1991)]].</ref> ''Dyfnwal'',<ref>[[#B1XXX|Broun (2015a)]]; [[#E2|Edmonds (2015)]]; [[#K2|Keynes (2015)]]; [[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]]; [[#E1|Edmonds (2014)]]; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]]; [[#C7|Clarkson (2012a)]]; [[#M10|Minard (2012)]]; [[#O2|Oram (2011)]]; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]]; [[#W4|Woolf (2009)]]; [[#BXX5|Breeze (2007)]]; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]]; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]]; [[#B12|Busse (2006c)]]; [[#M6|Minard (2006)]]; [[#B11|Broun (2004d)]]; [[#M1|Macquarrie (2004a)]]; [[#M3|Macquarrie (2004b)]]; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]]; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]]; [[#M2|Macquarrie (1998)]]; [[#W8|Woolf (1998)]] p. 190; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]].</ref> ''Dyfnwallon'',<ref>[[#W1|Woolf (2007)]]; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]]; [[#C16|Clancy (2002)]]; [[#M2|Macquarrie (1998)]].</ref> and ''Dwnwallon''.<ref name=\"C10\"/>|group=note}} He was a son of [[Owain ap Dyfnwal (fl. 934)|Owain ap Dyfnwal, King of Strathclyde]], and seems to have been a member of the royal dynasty of Strathclyde. At some point in the ninth- or tenth century, the [[Kingdom of Strathclyde]] expanded substantially southwards. As a result of this extension far beyond the valley of the [[River Clyde]], the realm became known as the [[Kingdom of Cumbria]]. By 927, the kingdom seems to have reached as far south as the [[River Eamont]].\n\nDyfnwal appears to have reigned between the 930s and the 970s. He is first attested in the 940s, when he is recorded associated with the ecclesiast [[Cathr\u00f3e of Metz|Cathr\u00f3e]] on the latter's journey to [[Continental Europe]]. At the midpoint of the decade, the Cumbrian kingdom was ravaged by the forces of [[Edmund, King of the English]]. Two of Dyfnwal's sons are said to have been blinded by the English, which could indicate that Dyfnwal had broken a pledge to his southern counterpart. One possibility is that he had harboured insular Scandinavian opponents of Edmund. The latter is recorded to have handed over control of the Cumbrian realm to [[M\u00e1el Coluim mac Domnaill, King of Alba]]. How much authority the Scots enjoyed over the Cumbrian realm is uncertain.\n\nIn 971, the reigning [[Cuil\u00e9n|Cuil\u00e9n mac Illuilb, King of Alba]] was slain by [[Rhydderch ap Dyfnwal]]. At some point after this act, Cuil\u00e9n's eventual successor, [[Cin\u00e1ed mac Ma\u00edl Choluim|Cin\u00e1ed mac Ma\u00edl Choluim, King of Alba]], is recorded to have penetrated deep into Cumbrian territory, possibly as a retaliatory act. The following year, the reigning [[Edgar, King of the English]] held a remarkable assembly at [[Chester]] which numerous northern kings seem to have attended. Both Dyfnwal and his son, [[M\u00e1el Coluim, King of Strathclyde|M\u00e1el Coluim]], appear to have attended this assembly. The latter is styled King of the Cumbrians in the context of this meeting, which might indicate that Dyfnwal had previously abdicated the throne.\n\nDyfnwal is recorded to have died in 975 whilst undertaking a pilgrimage to [[Rome]]. Quite when he gave up the throne is unknown. One possibility is that Rhydderch had succeeded him before the killing of Cuil\u00e9n. Another possibility is that the apparent retaliatory raid by Cin\u00e1ed marked the end of Dyfnwal's kingship. It is also possible that he held on to power until 973 or 975. In any event, M\u00e1el Coluim appears to have been succeeded by another son of Dyfnwal named [[Owain ap Dyfnwal (died 1015)|Owain]], who is recorded to have died in 1015. The later [[Owain Foel, King of Strathclyde]], who is attested in 1018, may well be a grandson of Dyfnwal. Dyfnwal is likely the [[eponym]] of [[Dunmail Raise]] in England, and possibly [[Cardonald]], [[Dundonald, South Ayrshire|Dundonald]]/[[Dundonald Castle]] in Scotland.\n\n==Background: the tenth century Cumbrian realm==\n\n[[File:Dyfnwal ab Owain (map).png|thumb|upright|alt=Map of northern Britain |Locations relating to the life and times of Dyfnwal.]]\n\nFor hundreds of years until the late ninth century, the power centre of the [[Kingdom of Al Clud]] was the fortress of [[Al Clud (fortress)|Al Clud]] (\"Rock of the Clyde\").<ref>[[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] p. 8; [[#C11|Clancy (2006)]].</ref> In 870, this [[Celtic Britons|British]] stronghold was [[Siege of Dumbarton|seized]] by Irish-based [[Vikings|Scandinavians]],<ref>[[#E2|Edmonds (2015)]] p. 44; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] pp. 9, 480; [[#C7|Clarkson (2012a)]] ch. 8 \u00b6 21; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 8 \u00b6 20; [[#D4|Davies (2009)]] p. 73; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] pp. 66, 142, 162; [[#C11|Clancy (2006)]]; [[#E5|Ewart; Pringle; Caldwell et al. (2004)]] p. 8.</ref> after which the centre of the realm seems to have relocated further up the [[River Clyde]], and the kingdom itself began to bear the name of the valley of the River Clyde, Ystrad Clud (Strathclyde).<ref>[[#D6|Driscoll, ST (2015)]] p. 5; [[#E2|Edmonds (2015)]] p. 44; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] pp. 9, 480\u2013481; [[#C7|Clarkson (2012a)]] ch. 8 \u00b6 23; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 8 \u00b6 26; [[#C11|Clancy (2006)]]; [[#E5|Ewart; Pringle; Caldwell et al. (2004)]] p. 8.</ref> The kingdom's new capital may have been situated in the vicinity of [[Partick]].<ref>[[#D6|Driscoll, ST (2015)]] pp. 5, 7; [[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 3 \u00b6 13; [[#C7|Clarkson (2012a)]] ch. 8 \u00b6 23; [[#C15|Clarkson (2012b)]] ch. 11 \u00b6 46; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 8 \u00b6 22; [[#E5|Ewart; Pringle; Caldwell et al. (2004)]] pp. 8, 10.</ref> and [[Govan]] which straddle the River Clyde,<ref>[[#F7|Foley (2017)]]; [[#D6|Driscoll, ST (2015)]] pp. 5, 7; [[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] chs. 1 \u00b6 23, 3 \u00b6 11\u201312; [[#E1|Edmonds (2014)]] p. 201; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] pp. 9, 480\u2013481; [[#C7|Clarkson (2012a)]] ch. 8 \u00b6 23; [[#C15|Clarkson (2012b)]] ch. 11 \u00b6 46; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 8 \u00b6 22; [[#D4|Davies (2009)]] p. 73; [[#O3|Oram (2008)]] p. 169; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] p. 169; [[#C11|Clancy (2006)]]; [[#D12|Driscoll, S (2006)]]; [[#F5|Forsyth (2005)]] p. 32; [[#E5|Ewart; Pringle; Caldwell et al. (2004)]] pp. 8, 10; [[#D7|Driscoll, ST (2003)]] pp. 81\u201382; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] pp. 32, 34; [[#D5|Driscoll, ST (2001a)]]; [[#D8|Driscoll, ST (2001b)]]; [[#D9|Driscoll, ST (1998)]] p. 112.</ref> The realm's new [[hinterland]] appears to have encompassed the valley and the region of modern [[Renfrewshire]], which may explain this change in terminology.<ref>[[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] pp. 480\u2013481.</ref>\n\n[[File:M\u00e1el Coluim mac Domnaill (British Library MS Cotton Faustina B IX, folio 9r).jpg|alt=Refer to caption|left|thumb|The title of Dyfnwal's son and eventual successor, [[M\u00e1el Coluim, King of Strathclyde|M\u00e1el Coluim]], as it appears on folio 9r of British Library Cotton Faustina B IX (the ''[[Chronicle of Melrose]]''): \"{{lang|la|rex Cumbrorum}}\".<ref name=\"combine1\">[[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 478; [[#S1|Stevenson, J (1856)]] p. 100; [[#S4|Stevenson, J (1835)]] p. 34; [[#C8|''Cotton MS Faustina B IX'' (n.d.)]].</ref>]]\n\nAt some point after the loss of Al Clud, the [[Kingdom of Strathclyde]] appears to have undergone a period of expansion.<ref>[[#D13|Dumville (2018)]] p. 118; [[#D6|Driscoll, ST (2015)]] pp. 6\u20137; [[#E2|Edmonds (2015)]] p. 44; [[#J8|James (2013)]] pp. 71\u201372; [[#P4|Parsons (2011)]] p. 123; [[#D4|Davies (2009)]] p. 73; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] pp. 160\u2013161, 161 n. 146; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 153; [[#BXX1|Breeze (2006)]] pp. 327, 331; [[#C11|Clancy (2006)]]; [[#E5|Ewart; Pringle; Caldwell et al. (2004)]] pp. 9\u201310; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] pp. 35\u201337, 36 n. 78.</ref> Although the precise chronology is uncertain, by 927 the southern frontier appears to have reached the [[River Eamont]], close to [[Penrith, Cumbria|Penrith]].<ref>[[#D13|Dumville (2018)]] pp. 72, 110, 118; [[#E2|Edmonds (2015)]] pp. 44, 53; [[#C17|Charles-Edwards (2013a)]] p. 20; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] pp. 9, 481; [[#P4|Parsons (2011)]] p. 138 n. 62; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 10; [[#D4|Davies (2009)]] p. 73, 73 n. 40; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] p. 165; [[#C11|Clancy (2006)]]; [[#T4|Todd (2005)]] p. 96; [[#S8|Stenton (1963)]] p. 328.</ref> The catalyst for this southern extension may have been the dramatic decline of the [[Kingdom of Northumbria]] at the hands of conquering Scandinavians,<ref>[[#L2|Lewis (2016)]] p. 15; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] pp. 9, 481\u2013482; [[#BXX1|Breeze (2006)]] pp. 327, 331; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] pp. 35\u201336, 36 n. 78; [[#W3|Woolf (2001)]]; [[#M2|Macquarrie (1998)]] p. 19; [[#F3|Fellows-Jensen (1991)]] p. 80.</ref> and the expansion may have been facilitated by cooperation between the Britons and the insular Scandinavians in the late ninth- or early tenth century.<ref>[[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] pp. 481\u2013482.</ref> Over time, the Kingdom of Strathclyde increasingly came to be known as the [[Kingdom of Cumbria]] reflecting its expansion far beyond the Clyde valley.<ref>[[#E2|Edmonds (2015)]] pp. 50\u201351; [[#M5|Molyneaux (2015)]] p. 15; [[#E1|Edmonds (2014)]]; [[#D4|Davies (2009)]] p. 73; [[#E4|Edmonds (2009)]] p. 44; [[#C11|Clancy (2006)]].</ref>{{#tag:ref|By about this time, the Cumbrian kingdom appears to have comprised much of modern [[Lanarkshire]], [[Dunbartonshire]], [[Renfrewshire]], [[Stirlingshire]], [[Peebleshire]], [[West Lothian]], [[Mid Lothian]], eastern [[Dumfriesshire]], and [[Cumberland]].<ref>[[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] pp. 154\u2013155.</ref> The [[Old English]] {{lang|ang|Cumbras}} is cognate with the [[Welsh language|Welsh]] {{lang|cy|Cymry}},<ref>[[#C11|Clancy (2006)]].</ref> a designation likely used by both the northern Britons and the more southerly Britons (the [[Welsh people|Welsh]]).<ref>[[#E2|Edmonds (2015)]] pp. 50\u201351; [[#E1|Edmonds (2014)]] pp. 201\u2013202; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] p. 2.</ref> Examples of the new terminology accorded to the northern realm include {{lang|ang|Cumbra land}} and {{lang|la|terra Cumbrorum}}, meaning \"land of the Cumbrians\".<ref>[[#E2|Edmonds (2015)]] pp. 50\u201352; [[#E1|Edmonds (2014)]] pp. 199\u2013200, 204\u2013205.</ref> Such 'Cumbrian' nomenclature is found in royal designations, suggesting that it reflected the realm's political expansion. By the mid tenth century, the 'Strathclyde' terminology seems to have been mostly superseded.<ref>[[#E1|Edmonds (2014)]].</ref> The expansion of the Cumbrian kingdom may be perceptible in some of the place names of southern Scotland and northern England.<ref>[[#J8|James (2013)]] p. 72; [[#J6|James (2011)]]; [[#J7|James (2009)]] p. 144, 144 n. 27; [[#M13|Millar (2009)]] p. 164.</ref>|group=note}}\n\n[[File:Dyfnwal ab Owain (Oxford Bodleian Library MS Rawlinson B 502, folio 25r).jpg|thumb|right|alt=Refer to caption|The names of Dyfnwal and his father, [[Owain ap Dyfnwal (fl. 934)|Owain ap Dyfnwal]], as they appear on folio 25r of [[Oxford Bodleian Library Rawlinson B 502]] (''[[Saltair na Rann]]''): \"{{lang|mga|Domnaill meic Eogain}}\".<ref>[[#M4|McGuigan (2015b)]] p. 140; [[#S5|''Saltair na Rann'' (2011)]] \u00a7\u00a7 2373\u20132376; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] pp. 101, 174 nn. 7\u20139; [[#M1002|Mac Eoin (1961)]] p. 53 \u00a7\u00a7 2373\u20132376, 55\u201356; [[#B2|''Bodleian Library MS. Rawl. B. 502'' (n.d.)]]; [[#S6|''Saltair na Rann'' (n.d.)]] \u00a7\u00a7 2373\u20132376.</ref>{{#tag:ref|The biblical poem ''Saltair na Rann'' seems to have been composed in the late tenth century.<ref>[[#H1|Hudson (2005)]] pp. 69, 220 n. 46; [[#H5|Hudson (1996)]] p. 102; [[#M1002|Mac Eoin (1961)]].</ref> The excerpt is that of a passage concerning Dyfnwal's son, M\u00e1el Coluim.<ref>[[#M4|McGuigan (2015b)]] p. 140; [[#S5|''Saltair na Rann'' (2011)]] \u00a7\u00a7 2373\u20132376; [[#H9|Hudson (2002)]] p. 36; [[#H5|Hudson (1996)]] p. 102; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] pp. 101, 174 nn. 7\u20139; [[#H12|Hudson (1991)]] p. 147; [[#S6|''Saltair na Rann'' (n.d.)]] \u00a7\u00a7 2373\u20132376.</ref>|group=note}}]]\n\nDyfnwal was a son of [[Owain ap Dyfnwal (fl. 934)|Owain ap Dyfnwal, King of Strathclyde]].<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. genealogical tables; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] p. 572 fig. 17.4; [[#M10|Minard (2012)]]; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. genealogical tables; [[#M6|Minard (2006)]]; [[#M2|Macquarrie (1998)]] p. 6; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 173 genealogy 6.</ref> The names of the latter and of his apparent descendants suggest that they were indeed members of the royal kindred of Strathclyde.<ref>[[#M2|Macquarrie (1998)]] pp. 14\u201315.</ref> Sons of Dyfnwal seem to include [[Rhydderch ap Dyfnwal|Rhydderch]],<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. genealogical tables; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] p. 572 fig. 17.4; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. genealogical tables; [[#B11|Broun (2004d)]] p. 135 tab.; [[#M2|Macquarrie (1998)]] pp. 6, 16; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 173 genealogy 6.</ref> [[M\u00e1el Coluim, King of Strathclyde|M\u00e1el Coluim]],<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. genealogical tables; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] p. 572 fig. 17.4; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. genealogical tables; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 238 tab. 6.4; [[#B11|Broun (2004d)]] p. 135 tab.; [[#M2|Macquarrie (1998)]] pp. 6, 16; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 173 genealogy 6.</ref> and [[Owain ap Dyfnwal (died 1015)|Owain]].<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. genealogical tables; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] p. 572 fig. 17.4; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. genealogical tables; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 236, 238 tab. 6.4; [[#B11|Broun (2004d)]] pp. 128 n. 66, 135 tab.</ref> The name of Dyfnwal's son M\u00e1el Coluim is [[Gaelic languages|Gaelic]], and may be evidence of a marriage alliance between his family and the neighbouring royal [[Alp\u00ednid dynasty]] of the Scottish [[Kingdom of Alba]].<ref>[[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 44.</ref> Dyfnwal's father is attested in 934.<ref>[[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 67 n. 65; [[#A3|Arnold (1882)]] p. 76 bk. 2 ch. 18; [[#SA4|Stevenson, J (1855)]] p. 669 ch. 33.</ref> Although Dyfnwal's father may well be identical to the Cumbrian monarch recorded to have fought at the [[Battle of Brunanburh]] in 937,<ref>[[#N1|Naismith (2017)]] p. 281; [[#O2|Oram (2011)]] ch. 2; [[#D2|Duncan (2002)]] p. 23 n. 53; [[#M2|Macquarrie (1998)]] p. 14; [[#W16|Williams; Smyth; Kirby (1991)]] p. 103; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 174 n. 7.</ref> the sources that note this king fail to identify him by name.<ref>[[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 67 n. 65; [[#A5|Anderson, AO (1908)]] pp. 70\u201371, 71 n. 3; [[#AA2|Arnold (1885)]] p. 93 ch. 83; [[#A3|Arnold (1882)]] p. 76 bk. 2 ch. 18; [[#SA4|Stevenson, J (1855)]] pp. 482, 669 ch. 33.</ref> Dyfnwal's own reign, therefore, may have stretched from about the 930s to the 970s.<ref name=\"T5-67\">[[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 67.</ref>{{#tag:ref|Only three kings are specifically termed \"King of the Cumbrians\" in historical sources: Dyfnwal's father, Dyfnwal himself, and Dyfnwal's son, M\u00e1el Coluim.<ref>[[#M6|Minard (2006)]].</ref>|group=note}}\n\n==Cathr\u00f3e amongst the Cumbrians==\n\n[[File:Eir\u00edkr Haraldsson (Oxford Bodleian Library MS Laud Miscellaneous 636, folio 36r).jpg|thumb|left|alt=Refer to caption|The name of Eir\u00edkr Haraldsson as it appears on folio 36r of Oxford Bodleian Library Laud Miscellaneous 636 (the \"[[Peterborough Chronicle|E]]\" version of the ''[[Anglo-Saxon Chronicle]]''): \"{{lang|ang|Yric Haroldes sunu}}\".<ref>[[#D1|Downham (2013)]] p. 202; [[#IX1|Irvine (2004)]] p. 55; [[#T6|Thorpe (1861)]] p. 215.</ref>]]\n\nDyfnwal is attested by the tenth-century ''Life of St Cathr\u00f3e'', which appears indicate that he was established as king by at least the 940s. According to this source, when [[Cathr\u00f3e of Metz|Cathr\u00f3e]] left the realm of [[Custant\u00edn mac \u00c1eda, King of Alba]] at about this time, he was granted safe passage through the lands of the Cumbrians by Dyfnwal because the two men were related. Dyfnwal thereupon had Cathr\u00f3e escorted through his kingdom to the frontier of the Scandinavian-controlled Northumbrian territory.<ref>[[#E3|Evans (2015)]] p. 150; [[#K2|Keynes (2015)]] p. 111; [[#M4|McGuigan (2015b)]] p. 98; [[#M5|Molyneaux (2015)]] p. 24, 24 n. 30; [[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] chs. 1 \u00b6 25, 6 \u00b6\u00b6 4\u20135; [[#E1|Edmonds (2014)]] pp. 205\u2013206; [[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 3 \u00b6 51; [[#C7|Clarkson (2012a)]] ch. 10 \u00b6 25; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 24; [[#B11|Broun (2004d)]] p. 127; [[#M1|Macquarrie (2004a)]]; [[#M3|Macquarrie (2004b)]]; [[#D3|Downham (2003)]] p. 27; [[#M2|Macquarrie (1998)]] pp. 15\u201316; [[#W8|Woolf (1998)]] p. 190; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 174 n. 8; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 441; [[#S3|Skene (1867)]] p. 116; [[#C4|Colganvm (1645)]] p. 497 \u00a7 xvii.</ref> The ''Life of St Cathr\u00f3e'' locates this southern frontier to the {{lang|la|civitas}} of {{lang|la|Loida}}. One possibility is that this refers to [[Leeds]]. If correct, this could indicate that the Cumbrian realm stretched towards this settlement, and would further evince the general southward expansion of the kingdom.<ref>[[#M5|Molyneaux (2015)]] p. 24, 24 n. 30; [[#E1|Edmonds (2014)]] p. 206 n. 59; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] p. 38.</ref> Another possibility is that {{lang|la|Loida}} refers to [[Leath Ward]] in Cumberland,<ref>[[#E1|Edmonds (2014)]] p. 206 n. 59; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] p. 38.</ref> or to a settlement in the [[Lowther, Cumbria|Lowther]] valley, not terribly from where the River Eamont flows.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 \u00b6 5; [[#E1|Edmonds (2014)]] p. 206 n. 59; [[#C7|Clarkson (2012a)]] ch. 10 \u00b6 25; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 24.</ref>\n\n[[File:Anlaff Entering the Humber.jpg|upright|thumb|right|alt=Black and white illustration of Viking king, looking out from his warship, at the head of his fleet.|An early twentieth-century depiction of [[Amla\u00edb mac Gofraid (died 941)|Amla\u00edb mac Gofraid]] campaigning against the English in 937.<ref>[[#C2|''Cassell's History of England'' (1909)]] p. 49.</ref>{{#tag:ref|If Dyfnwal's father is identical to the Cumbrian king who fought at the Battle of Brunanburh, he would have been allied to Amla\u00edb mac Gofraid in this conflict.<ref>[[#N1|Naismith (2017)]] p. 281; [[#H6|Hudson (2004)]]; [[#D2|Duncan (2002)]] p. 23 n. 53; [[#M2|Macquarrie (1998)]] p. 14.</ref> The latter may have been the father of Maccus mac Amla\u00edb, an otherwise unknown figure said to have slain Eir\u00edkr Haraldsson at [[Stainmore]] in 954.<ref>[[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] pp. 120\u2013121, 121 n. 79; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 190; [[#H6|Hudson (2004)]].</ref>|group=note}}]]\n\nThe ''Life of St Cathr\u00f3e'' identifies Cathr\u00f3e's parents as Fochereach and Bania.<ref>[[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 24; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] pp. 431\u2013432, 431 n. 6; [[#S3|Skene (1867)]] p. 109; [[#C4|Colganvm (1645)]] pp. 495 \u00a7 vi, 502\u2013503 n. 42, 503 n. 43.</ref> Whilst the former's name is Gaelic, the latter's name could be either Gaelic or [[British language (Celtic)|British]],<ref name=\"C3-924\">[[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 24.</ref> and Cathr\u00f3e's own name could be either [[Pictish language|Pictish]]<ref name=\"M1\"/> or British.<ref>[[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 24; [[#M1|Macquarrie (2004a)]].</ref> The fact that Cathr\u00f3e is stated to have been related to Dyfnwal could indicate that the former's ancestors included a Briton who possessed a genealogical connection with the royal Cumbrian dynasty,<ref>[[#C7|Clarkson (2012a)]] ch. 10 \u00b6 25; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 24.</ref> or that Dyfnwal possessed Scottish ancestry, or else that the families of Cathr\u00f3e and Dyfnwal were merely connected by way of a marriage.<ref name=\"C3-924\"/> Cathr\u00f3e is also said by the source to have been related to the wife of a certain [[King of York]] named Erich.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 \u00b6\u00b6 4\u20136, 6 n. 6; [[#E1|Edmonds (2014)]] pp. 205\u2013206; [[#D1|Downham (2013)]] pp. 187, 203; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] p. 119; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] pp. 187\u2013188; [[#C12|Costambeys (2004)]]; [[#M1|Macquarrie (2004a)]]; [[#W8|Woolf (1998)]] p. 193 n. 18; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 441; [[#S3|Skene (1867)]] p. 116; [[#C4|Colganvm (1645)]] p. 497 \u00a7 xvii.</ref> Although the latter may be identical to Eir\u00edkr Haraldsson\u2014a man who is generally thought to be identical to the Norwegian dynast [[Eir\u00edkr bl\u00f3\u00f0\u00f8x]]<ref>[[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 24; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] pp. 187\u2013188; [[#M1|Macquarrie (2004a)]]; [[#W17|Woolf (2002)]] p. 39; [[#W8|Woolf (1998)]].</ref>\u2014this man is not otherwise attested by insular sources until 947, and Northumbria itself appears to have been ruled by the [[U\u00ed \u00cdmair]] dynasts [[Amla\u00edb mac Gofraid (died 941)|Amla\u00edb mac Gofraid]] and [[Amla\u00edb C\u00faar\u00e1n]] during the time of Cathr\u00f3e's journey.<ref>[[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] pp. 187\u2013188.</ref> Whilst it is possible that Erich actually refers to Amla\u00edb mac Gofraid,<ref name=\"M1\"/> if he instead refers to Eir\u00edkr Haraldsson, it could be evidence that the latter had been based in the [[Solway Firth|Solway]] region whilst the [[U\u00ed \u00cdmair]] held power in Northumbria,<ref>[[#W8|Woolf (1998)]] p. 193 n. 18.</ref> or that the latter indeed held power in Northumbria as early as about 946.<ref>[[#D3|Downham (2003)]] pp. 43, 49.</ref>{{#tag:ref|There is reason to suspect that Eir\u00edkr bl\u00f3\u00f0\u00f8x and Eir\u00edkr Haraldsson have been conflated,<ref>[[#N1|Naismith (2017)]] p. 281; [[#J4|Jakobsson (2016)]] p. 173; [[#M12|McGuigan (2015a)]] p. 31, 31 n. 48; [[#D1|Downham (2013)]]; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] pp. 115\u2013120, 120 n. 74; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] pp. 187\u2013188; [[#W17|Woolf (2002)]] p. 39.</ref> and that the latter man was actually a member of the insular U\u00ed \u00cdmair.<ref>[[#N1|Naismith (2017)]] pp. 281, 300\u2013301; [[#M12|McGuigan (2015a)]] p. 31, 31 n. 48; [[#D1|Downham (2013)]]; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] pp. 119\u2013120, 120 n. 74; [[#W17|Woolf (2002)]] p. 39.</ref> For example, Scandinavian sources fail to accord Eir\u00edkr bl\u00f3\u00f0\u00f8x an insular wife as laid out by ''Life of St Cathr\u00f3e''. The record of this marriage is some of the evidence hinting that Eir\u00edkr bl\u00f3\u00f0\u00f8x has been erroneously linked with Northumbria since the twelfth century.<ref>[[#D1|Downham (2013)]]; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] pp. 115\u2013120, 120 n. 74.</ref>|group=note}}\n\n==English aggression and Scottish overlordship==\n\n[[File:Kingdom of the Cumbrians (British Library Cotton MS Tiberius B I, folio 142r).jpg|thumb|left|alt=Refer to caption|The terminology employed for Dyfnwal's realm as it appears on folio 142r of British Library Cotton Tiberius B I (the \"C\" version of the ''Anglo-Saxon Chronicle''): \"{{lang|ang|Cumbra land}}{{-\"}}.<ref>[[#O1|O'Keeffe (2001)]] p. 80; [[#W9|Whitelock (1996)]] p. 224, 224 n. 2; [[#T6|Thorpe (1861)]] p. 212; [[#C6|''Cotton MS Tiberius B I'' (n.d.)]].</ref>]]\n\nIn 945, the \"A\" version of the eleventh- to thirteenth-century ''[[Annales Cambri\u00e6]]'',<ref>[[#G2|Gough-Cooper (2015a)]] p. 27 \u00a7 a509.3; [[#K2|Keynes (2015)]] pp. 95\u201396; [[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 \u00b6 14, 6 n. 19; [[#H11|Halloran (2011)]] p. 308, 308 n. 40; [[#W6|Woolf (2010)]] p. 228, 228 n. 27; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] p. 153; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 183; [[#D3|Downham (2003)]] p. 42; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] p. 39; [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] p. 114; [[#A10|Alcock (1975\u20131976)]] p. 106; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 449.</ref> and the thirteenth- and fourteenth-century ''[[Brut y Tywysogyon]]'' reveal that the Cumbrian realm was wasted by the English.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 \u00b6 15; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 25; [[#D3|Downham (2003)]] p. 42; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] p. 39; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 449; [[#R1|Rh\u0177s (1890)]] p. 261; [[#W7|Williams Ab Ithel (1860)]] pp. 20\u201321.</ref> The ninth- to twelfth-century ''[[Anglo-Saxon Chronicle]]'' offers more information, and relates that [[Edmund I, King of the English]] harried across the land of the Cumbrians, and {{lang|ang|let}} the region to [[M\u00e1el Coluim mac Domnaill, King of Alba]].<ref>[[#G2|Gough-Cooper (2015a)]] p. 27 n. 191; [[#K2|Keynes (2015)]] pp. 95\u201396; [[#M4|McGuigan (2015b)]] pp. 83, 139\u2013140; [[#M8|McLeod (2015)]] p. 4; [[#M5|Molyneaux (2015)]] pp. 33, 52\u201353, 76; [[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] chs. 1 \u00b6 10, 6 \u00b6 11, 6 n. 18, 6 \u00b6 20; [[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 5; [[#H11|Halloran (2011)]] p. 307, 307 n. 36; [[#M7|Molyneaux (2011)]] pp. 66, 66 n. 27, 69, 70, 73, 88; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6\u00b6 25\u201327; [[#W6|Woolf (2010)]] p. 228, 228 n. 26; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] p. 153; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 183; [[#C11|Clancy (2006)]]; [[#W13|Williams (2004c)]]; [[#D3|Downham (2003)]] p. 42; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] p. 16 n. 35; [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 114\u2013115, 114 n. 29; [[#D2|Duncan (2002)]] p. 23; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 78, 78 n. 114; [[#O1|O'Keeffe (2001)]] p. 80; [[#W5|Williams (1999)]] p. 86; [[#W9|Whitelock (1996)]] p. 224; [[#S9|Smyth (1989)]] pp. 205\u2013206; [[#R2|Rose (1982)]] pp. 119, 122; [[#A10|Alcock (1975\u20131976)]] p. 106; [[#S8|Stenton (1963)]] p. 355; [[#A5|Anderson, AO (1908)]] p. 74, 74 n. 3; [[#T6|Thorpe (1861)]] pp. 212\u2013213.</ref> Similarly, the twelfth-century ''[[Historia Anglorum (Henry of Huntingdon)|Historia Anglorum]]'' records that the English ravaged the realm, and that Edmund commended the lands to M\u00e1el Coluim mac Domnaill who had agreed to assist him by land and sea.<ref>[[#H10|Holland (2016)]] ch. Malmesbury \u00b6 7; [[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 \u00b6 11, 6 n. 20; [[#A5|Anderson, AO (1908)]] p. 74 nn. 4\u20135; [[#A4|Arnold (1879)]] p. 162 bk. 5 ch. 21; [[#F2|Forester (1853)]] p. 172 bk. 5.</ref> According to the version of events preserved by the thirteenth-century [[Flores historiarum (Wendover)|Wendover]]<ref>[[#F6|Firth (2016)]] pp. 24\u201325; [[#M4|McGuigan (2015b)]] p. 139; [[#M5|Molyneaux (2015)]] pp. 33, 61, 76; [[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 \u00b6\u00b6 12\u201313, 6 n. 21; [[#H11|Halloran (2011)]] p. 308; [[#M7|Molyneaux (2011)]] pp. 66, 66 n. 27, 70; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 183; [[#D2|Duncan (2002)]] p. 23;  [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] p. 114; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 78, 78 n. 114; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 174 n. 12; [[#S8|Stenton (1963)]] p. 355; [[#A5|Anderson, AO (1908)]] p. 74 n. 5; [[#G3|Giles (1849)]] pp. 252\u2013253; [[#C5|Coxe (1841)]] p. 398.</ref> and [[Flores historiarum (Paris)|Paris]] versions of ''Flores historiarum'', Edmund was assisted in the campaign by [[Hywel Dda, King of Dyfed]], and had two of Dyfnwal's sons blinded.<ref>[[#M4|McGuigan (2015b)]] p. 139; [[#L1|Luard (2012)]] p. 500; [[#H11|Halloran (2011)]] p. 308, 308 n. 41; [[#Y1|Yonge (1853)]] p. 473.</ref> If the latter claim is to be believed, it could reveal that the two princes had been English hostages before hostilities broke out, or perhaps prisoners captured in the midst of the campaign.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 \u00b6 14; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 25.</ref>{{#tag:ref|The ritual blinding of kings was not an unknown act in contemporary Britain and Ireland,<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 n. 23.</ref> and it is possible that Edmund may have also meant to deprive Dyfnwal of a royal heir.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] chs. 6 \u00b6 14, 7 \u00b6 5.</ref>|group=note}} The gruesome fate inflicted upon these sons could reveal that their father was regarded to have broken certain pledges rendered to the English.<ref>[[#H10|Holland (2016)]] ch. Malmesbury \u00b6 5; [[#M5|Molyneaux (2015)]] pp. 77\u201378; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 183 p. 183.</ref> One possibility is that Dyfnwal was punished for harbouring insular Scandinavian potentates<ref>[[#O2|Oram (2011)]] ch. 2.</ref> such as Amla\u00edb C\u00faar\u00e1n.<ref>[[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 183.</ref> The latter is certainly recorded to have been driven from Northumbria by the English the year before.<ref>[[#M5|Molyneaux (2015)]] p. 31; [[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 \u00b6 11; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] pp. 182\u2013183; [[#D3|Downham (2003)]] p. 41; [[#W9|Whitelock (1996)]] p. 224.</ref> He could well have taken refuge amongst the Cumbrians,<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 \u00b6 16; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] pp. 182\u2013183.</ref> or may have been attempting to construct a power base in the Cumbrian periphery.<ref>[[#W17|Woolf (2002)]] p. 38.</ref> The close working relationship between Edmund and M\u00e1el Coluim mac Domnaill suggests that Amla\u00edb C\u00faar\u00e1n was unlikely to have been harboured by the Scots during this period.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 \u00b6 16.</ref> Edmund's strike upon Dyfnwal's realm, therefore, seems to have been undertaken as a means to break a Cumbrian-Scandinavian alliance,<ref>[[#F8|Fulton (2000)]] pp. 11, 13.</ref> and to limit the threat of an insular Scandinavian counter offensive from the [[Firth of Forth|Forth]]-[[Firth of Clyde|Clyde]] region.<ref>[[#D3|Downham (2003)]] p. 42; [[#S9|Smyth (1989)]] pp. 205\u2013206.</ref> The southward expansion of the Cumbrian realm\u2014an extension possibly enabled by the insular Scandinavian power\u2014may have also factored into the invasion, with the English clawing back lost territories.<ref>[[#H11|Halloran (2011)]] p. 307.</ref> Whatever lay behind the campaign, it is possible that it was utilised by the English [[Cerdicing dynasty]] as a way to overawe and intimidate neighbouring potentates.<ref>[[#M5|Molyneaux (2015)]] pp. 33, 77\u201378.</ref>\n\n[[File:The Giant's Grave, Penrith, Cumbria (geograph 4876739).jpg|thumb|right|alt=Refer to caption|The Giant's Grave, a collection of apparent tenth-century monuments at [[Penrith, Cumbria|Penrith]]. The stones display significant Scandinavian influences, and are traditionally associated with a legendary king, variably known as Owain Caesarius. It is possible that this figure refers to Dyfnwal's father or son.<ref>[[#E2|Edmonds (2015)]] p. 5, 55 n. 61; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 10 \u00b6 11; [[#P2|''Proceedings'' (1947)]] pp. 221\u2013225; [[#CZZZ1|Collingwood (1923)]].</ref>]]\n\nAlthough the Wendover version of ''Flores historiarum'' alleges that M\u00e1el Coluim mac Domnaill was given Cumbrian territory to hold as a fief from the English, the terminology employed by the more reliable ''Anglo-Saxon Chronicle'' seems to suggest that Edmund merely surrendered or granted the region to him,<ref>[[#H11|Halloran (2011)]] p. 307; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] pp. 183\u2013184.</ref> or that he merely recognised certain rights of the Scots in the region (such as the right to tribute).<ref>[[#M4|McGuigan (2015b)]] pp. 139\u2013140; [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] p. 115 n. 32; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] pp. 84\u201385.</ref> Edmund, therefore, may have allowed his Scottish counterpart to collect tribute from the Cumbrians in return for keeping them in check and for lending Edmund military assistance.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 \u00b6 20.</ref> It is possible that the territory in question corresponds to the region around [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]]\u2014roughly modern-day [[Cumberland]]\u2014which in turn could reveal that the Scots were already in possession of the kingdom's more northerly lands.<ref>[[#D2|Duncan (2002)]] p. 23.</ref> It is conceivable that the Scots were allowed authority over Cumbrian territory because it was too far to be overseen effectively by the English themselves.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 \u00b6 20; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 184.</ref> As such, it may have been recognised that the Cumbrian territories were situated within the Alp\u00ednid sphere of influence rather than that of the Cerdicings.<ref>[[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] p. 116, 116 n. 36.</ref> In any event, it is uncertain what authority M\u00e1el Coluim mac Domnaill enjoyed over the Cumbrians. Although it is possible that there was a temporary Scottish takeover of the realm,<ref>[[#P4|Parsons (2011)]] p. 129; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 184.</ref> Dyfnwal lived on for decades, and there were certainly later kings.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 \u00b6 21; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 184.</ref> In fact, the Wendover version ''Flores historiarum'' reveals that the Cumbrians were ruled by a king the year after Edmund's invasion.<ref>[[#M4|McGuigan (2015b)]] p. 139; [[#G3|Giles (1849)]] pp. 253\u2013254; [[#C5|Coxe (1841)]] p. 399.</ref> The concord between the English and the Scots could have been precipitated by the former as a way of further securing their northern frontier from the threat of insular Scandinavians.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 \u00b6 20; [[#M7|Molyneaux (2011)]] p. 76; [[#W13|Williams (2004c)]]; [[#D3|Downham (2003)]] p. 42; [[#S9|Smyth (1989)]] pp. 205\u2013206.</ref> Similarly, the English campaign against the Cumbrians may have been undertaken in order to isolate the Scots from an alliance with the Scandinavians.<ref>[[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] p. 153.</ref> In this way, Edmund's conquest and grant of Cumbrian territories to his Scottish counterpart may have been a way of winning the latter's obeisance.<ref>[[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] p. 153; [[#F8|Fulton (2000)]] p. 13.</ref>\n\n[[File:Scots, Cumbrians, and English (Oxford Bodleian Library MS Rawlinson B 489, folio 32r).jpg|thumb|left|alt=Refer to caption|The terminology used to denote an alliance of Scots, Cumbrians, and Englishmen, on folio 32r of Oxford Bodleian Library Rawlinson B 489 (the ''[[Annals of Ulster]]'').<ref>[[#T2|''The Annals of Ulster'' (2017)]] \u00a7 952.2; [[#T1|''The Annals of Ulster'' (2008)]] \u00a7 952.2; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 451; [[#B14|''Bodleian Library MS. Rawl. B. 489'' (n.d.)]].</ref>]]\n\nEdmund was assassinated in 946, and succeeded by his brother [[Eadred]], a monarch who soon after made a show of force against opposition in Northumbria,<ref>[[#M4|McGuigan (2015b)]] pp. 83\u201384; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 28; [[#W12|Williams (2004b)]]; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 450.</ref> and received a renewal of oaths from his Scottish counterpart.<ref>[[#M4|McGuigan (2015b)]] pp. 83\u201384; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 28; [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 116\u2013117; [[#F8|Fulton (2000)]] p. 14.</ref> In about 949/950, M\u00e1el Coluim mac Domnaill is recorded to have raided into Northumbria, perhaps against the retrenched forces of Eadred's Scandinavian opponents.<ref>[[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 28; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] pp. 154\u2013155; [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] p. 131, 131 n. 103; [[#H4|Hudson (1998)]] pp. 150\u2013151, 158; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] pp. 86\u201387; [[#S3|Skene (1867)]] p. 10.</ref> Whilst it is possible that this event was undertaken in the context of compensation for the English campaigning against the Cumbrians in 946,<ref>[[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] p. 131; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] pp. 86\u201387.</ref> an alternate possibility is that this Scottish invasion was instead an opportunistic attempt to extract tribute from the Northumbrian ruler [[Osulf I of Bamburgh|Osulf]] (fl. 946\u2013950), rather than the York-based Scandinavians.<ref>[[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 131\u2013132.</ref>\n\nIn 952, the seventeenth-century ''[[Annals of the Four Masters]]''<ref>[[#A7|''Annals of the Four Masters'' (2013a)]] \u00a7 950.14; [[#A8|''Annals of the Four Masters'' (2013b)]] \u00a7 950.14; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] p. 155; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 451 n. 4.</ref> and the fifteenth- to sixteenth-century ''[[Annals of Ulster]]'' appear to report an attack upon the Scandinavians of Northumbria by an alliance of English, Scots, and Cumbrians.<ref>[[#T2|''The Annals of Ulster'' (2017)]] \u00a7 952.2; [[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 10; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 28; [[#T1|''The Annals of Ulster'' (2008)]] \u00a7 952.2; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] pp. 155, 167; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 188\u2013189; [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 60, 132, 132 n. 108; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 87; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 451.</ref> If these two annal-entries indeed refer to Cumbrians rather than [[Welsh people|Welshmen]], it would appear to indicate that the former\u2014presumably led by Dyfnwal himself\u2014were supporting the cause of the English with the Scots.<ref>[[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 28; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] pp. 188\u2013189.</ref> One possibility is that the annal-entries record the clash of this coalition against the forces of Eir\u00edkr, a man who was finally overwhelmed and slain two years later.<ref>[[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] p. 155; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] pp. 188\u2013189; [[#C12|Costambeys (2004)]]; [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 132\u2013133; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 87.</ref>\n\n[[File:Dyfnwal ab Owain (Oxford Bodleian Library MS Jesus College 111, folio 59r).jpg|thumb|right|alt=Refer to caption|Dyfnwal's name as it appears on folio 59r of Oxford Jesus College 111 (the ''[[Red Book of Hergest]]''): \"{{lang|wlm|d\u1efdnwa\u1efba\u1efdn}}\".<ref>[[#R1|Rh\u0177s (1890)]] p. 262; [[#W7|Williams Ab Ithel (1860)]] pp. 26\u201327; [[#J5|''Jesus College MS. 111'' (n.d.)]]; [[#O5|''Oxford Jesus College MS. 111'' (n.d.)]].</ref>]]\n\nThere is also reason to suspect that a man other than Dyfnwal ruled as king in the wake of Edmund's 945 campaign. For instance, a certain Cadmon is recorded to have witnessed two royal charters of Edmund's successor, Eadred\u2014one in 946 and another in 949\u2014which could be evidence that Cadmon was then the ruling Cumbrian monarch.<ref>[[#K2|Keynes (2015)]] pp. 84\u201385 fig. 1, 100\u2013101, 100 n. 131; [[#M5|Molyneaux (2015)]] pp. 57 n. 45, 212, 212 n. 83; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] pp. 515 tab. 16.1, 516\u2013517; [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 118\u2013119; [[#P3|Pierquin (1912)]] pp. 294\u2013295 \u00a7 86, 303\u2013304 \u00a7 94; [[#BXX4|Birch (1893)]] pp. 38\u201340 \u00a7 883; [[#B5|Birch (1887)]] pp. 576\u2013578 \u00a7 815; [[#C16|''Cadfan 1'' (n.d.)]]; [[#S14|''S 544'' (n.d.)]]; [[#S13|''S 520'' (n.d.)]].</ref> There may be evidence indicating that, from about the time of the campaign until at least 958, the English regarded the land of the Cumbrians to be a part of the English realm.<ref>[[#K2|Keynes (2015)]] pp. 96 n. 110, 107.</ref> For instance, a charter apparently issued upon Eadred's coronation\u2014the first of the two witnessed by Cadmon\u2014accords Eadred the title \"king of the Anglo-Saxons, Northumbrians, pagans, and Britons\";<ref>[[#K2|Keynes (2015)]] pp. 98\u201399, 119\u2013120; [[#K4|Keynes (2001)]] p. 70; [[#P3|Pierquin (1912)]] pp. 294\u2013295 \u00a7 86; [[#B5|Birch (1887)]] pp. 576\u2013578 \u00a7 815; [[#S13|''S 520'' (n.d.)]].</ref> whilst a 958 charter of Eadred's royal successor [[Edgar, King of the English|Edgar]], accords the latter kingship over \"the Mercians, Northumbrians and Britons\".<ref>[[#K2|Keynes (2015)]] p. 120; [[#K4|Keynes (2001)]] p. 72; [[#BXX4|Birch (1893)]] pp. 242\u2013244 \u00a7 1040; [[#S15|''S 677'' (n.d.)]].</ref> The fact that the ''acta'' of Edmund, Eadred, and Edgar fail to record the presence of Dyfnwal could be evidence of English rule over the Cumbrians, who may have been in turn administered by English-aligned agents.<ref>[[#K2|Keynes (2015)]] p. 107.</ref>\n\n==Cumbrian and Scottish contention==\n\n[[File:Illulb mac Custant\u00edn (Lat. 4126, folio 29v).jpg|thumb|left|alt=Refer to caption|The name of [[Illulb mac Custant\u00edn]] as it appears on 29v of Paris Biblioth\u00e8que Nationale Latin 4126 (the ''[[Poppleton manuscript]]''): \"{{lang|la|Indolf filius Constantini}}{{-\"}}.<ref name=\"pop1\">[[#H8|Howlett (2000)]] p. 65; [[#S3|Skene (1867)]] p. 131; [[#L3|''Lat. 4126'' (n.d.)]] fol. 29v.</ref>]]\n\nM\u00e1el Coluim mac Domnaill was slain in 954, and succeeded by [[Illulb mac Custant\u00edn]].<ref>[[#BXX2|Broun (2004b)]]; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] pp. 88\u201389.</ref> At some point during the latter's reign, the Scots permanently acquired [[Edinburgh]] from the English,<ref>[[#T8|Taylor (2016)]] pp. 8\u20139; [[#BXX3|Broun (2015b)]]; [[#BXX2|Broun (2004b)]]; [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] p. 133.</ref> as partly evidenced by the ninth- to twelfth-century ''[[Chronicle of the Kings of Alba]]''.<ref>[[#T8|Taylor (2016)]] pp. 8\u20139; [[#M4|McGuigan (2015b)]] pp. 148\u2013149; [[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 \u00b6 35; [[#H4|Hudson (1998)]] pp. 151, 159; [[#D2|Duncan (2002)]] p. 23; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] pp. 89\u201390; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 468; [[#S3|Skene (1867)]] p. 10.</ref> Confirmation of this conquest seems to be preserved by the twelfth-century ''[[Historia regum Anglorum]]'', a source which states that, during the reign of [[Edgar, King of the English]], the Northumbrian frontier extended as far as the {{lang|la|Tin\u00e6}}, a waterway which seems to refer to the [[River Tyne, Scotland|River Tyne]] in Lothian.<ref>[[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 89; [[#AA2|Arnold (1885)]] p. 197 ch. 159; [[#SA4|Stevenson, J (1855)]] p. 557.</ref> The acquisition of Edinburgh, and extension into Lothian itself, may well to have taken place during the reign of the embattled and unpopular [[Eadwig, King of the English]].<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 \u00b6 35; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] pp. 89\u201390.</ref> Illulb's attack may be evidenced by passages preserved by the twelfth-century ''[[Prophecy of Berch\u00e1n]]'' which not only note \"woe\" inflicted upon the Britons and English, but also the conquest of foreign territories by way of Scottish military might.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 \u00b6\u00b6 35\u201336; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 29; [[#H4|Hudson (1998)]] p. 159 n. 57; [[#H5|Hudson (1996)]] pp. 48 \u00a7 160, 48 \u00a7 162, 88 \u00a7 160, 88 \u00a7 162, 88 n. 97; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] pp. 89\u201390; [[#A9|Anderson, AO (1930)]] pp. 46 \u00a7 158; 46\u201347 \u00a7 160; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 471; [[#S3|Skene (1867)]] p. 94.</ref> The notice of Britons in this text could be evidence that Illulb campaigned against Cumbrian-controlled territories.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 \u00b6\u00b6 35\u201336; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] pp. 89\u201390.</ref> Such conflict may have meant that the apparent Cumbrian extension southwards was mirrored by movement eastwards. One possibility is that the Scots seized Edinburgh not from the English but from Cumbrians who had temporarily taken possession of it. Certainly, the fortress of Edinburgh had anciently been a British stronghold.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 \u00b6 36.</ref>\n\n==Rhydderch, son of Dyfnwal==\n\n[[File:Rhydderch ap Dyfnwal (British Library MS Cotton Faustina B IX, folio 8v).jpg|alt=Refer to caption|right|thumb|The name of [[Rhydderch ap Dyfnwal]], as it appears on folio 8v of British Library Cotton Faustina B IX: \"{{lang|la|Radhardus}}{{-\"}}.<ref>[[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 476; [[#S4|Stevenson, J (1835)]] p. 226; [[#C8|''Cotton MS Faustina B IX'' (n.d.)]].</ref>]]\n\nAfter Illulb's death in 962, the Scottish kingship appears to have been taken up by [[Dub mac Ma\u00edl Choluim]], a man who was in turn replaced by Illulb's son, [[Cuil\u00e9n]].<ref>[[#B4|Broun (2004a)]].</ref> The latter's death at the hands of Britons in 971 is recorded by several sources. Some of these sources locate his death to locations that could refer to either [[Abington, South Lanarkshire|Abington in South Lanarkshire]],<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 6; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 32; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] pp. 40\u201341; [[#M2|Macquarrie (1998)]] p. 16 n. 3; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 476 n. 2.</ref> [[Lothian]],<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 6; [[#C7|Clarkson (2012a)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 28; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 34.</ref> or [[the Lennox]].<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 6; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 34.</ref> There is reason to suspect that Cuil\u00e9n's killer was a son of Dyfnwal himself.<ref>[[#B1XXX|Broun (2015a)]]; [[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 6; [[#C7|Clarkson (2012a)]] ch. 9 \u00b6\u00b6 28\u201329; [[#O2|Oram (2011)]] chs. 2, 5; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 34; [[#BZZ1|Busse (2006b)]]; [[#B12|Busse (2006c)]]; [[#B11|Broun (2004d)]] p. 135 tab.; [[#M3|Macquarrie (2004b)]]; [[#M2|Macquarrie (1998)]] pp. 6, 16; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] pp. 173 genealogy 6, 174 n. 10; [[#W16|Williams; Smyth; Kirby (1991)]] pp. 92, 104.</ref> The ''Chronicle of the Kings of Alba'' reports that the killer was a certain [[Rhydderch ap Dyfnwal]], a man who slew Cuil\u00e9n for the sake of his own daughter.<ref>[[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 32; [[#M2|Macquarrie (1998)]] p. 16; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 476, 476 n. 1; [[#S3|Skene (1867)]] p. 151.</ref> The thirteenth-century ''Verse Chronicle'',<ref>[[#B1|Broun (2005)]] pp. 87\u201388 n. 37; [[#S3|Skene (1867)]] p. 179.</ref> the twelfth- to thirteenth-century ''[[Chronicle of Melrose]]'',<ref>[[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6\u00b6 32\u201333; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 204; [[#M3|Macquarrie (2004b)]]; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] pp. 40\u201341; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 476; [[#S4|Stevenson, J (1835)]] p. 226.</ref> and the fourteenth-century ''[[Chronica gentis Scotorum]]'' likewise identify Cuil\u00e9n's killer as Rhydderch, the father of an abducted daughter raped by the Scottish king.<ref>[[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] pp. 93, 174 n. 10; [[#S2|Skene (1872)]] pp. 161\u2013162 bk. 4 ch. 27; [[#S10|Skene (1871)]] pp. 169\u2013170 bk 4.</ref>\n\n[[File:Cuil\u00e9n mac Illuilb (Lat. 4126, folio 29v) 2.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Refer to caption|The name of [[Cuil\u00e9n|Cuil\u00e9n mac Illuilb]] as it appears on folio 29v of Paris Biblioth\u00e8que Nationale Latin 4126: \"{{lang|la|Culen filius Indulf}}{{-\"}}.<ref name=\"pop1\"/>]]\n\nAlthough there is no specific evidence that Rhydderch was himself a king,<ref>[[#M3|Macquarrie (2004b)]]; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 67 n. 66.</ref> the fact that Cuil\u00e9n was involved with his daughter, coupled with the fact that his warband was evidently strong enough to overcome that of Cuil\u00e9n, suggests that Rhydderch must have been a man of eminent standing.<ref>[[#M3|Macquarrie (2004b)]].</ref> According to the ''Prophecy of Berch\u00e1n'', Cuil\u00e9n met his end whilst \"seeking a foreign land\", which could indicate that he was attempting to lift taxes from the Cumbrians.<ref>[[#H4|Hudson (1998)]] p. 160 n. 71; [[#M2|Macquarrie (1998)]] p. 16; [[#H5|Hudson (1996)]] pp. 49 \u00a7 168, 88 \u00a7 168; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 93; [[#A9|Anderson, AO (1930)]] p. 48 \u00a7 166; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 477; [[#S3|Skene (1867)]] pp. 95\u201396.</ref> Another way in which Cuil\u00e9n may have met his end concerns the record of his father's seizure of Edinburgh. The fact that this conquest would have likely included at least part of Lothian,<ref>[[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6\u00b6 16\u201318, 24; [[#H4|Hudson (1998)]] pp. 151, 159; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 468; [[#S3|Skene (1867)]] p. 10.</ref> coupled with the evidence locating Cuil\u00e9n's demise to the same area, could indicate that Cuil\u00e9n was slain in the midst of exercising overlordship of this contested territory. If so, the records that link Rhydderch with the [[regicide]] could reveal that this wronged father exploited Cuil\u00e9n's vulnerable position in the region, and that Rhydderch seized the chance to avenge his daughter.<ref>[[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 24.</ref>\n\n[[File:Cin\u00e1ed mac Ma\u00edl Choluim (Oxford Bodleian Library MS Rawlinson B 488, folio 15r).jpg|thumb|right|alt=Refer to caption|The name of Cuil\u00e9n's apparent successor, [[Cin\u00e1ed mac Ma\u00edl Choluim]], as it appears on folio 15r of Oxford Bodleian Library Rawlinson B 488: \"{{lang|mga|Cinaeth mac Mail Cholaim}}\".<ref>[[#T3|''The Annals of Tigernach'' (2016)]] \u00a7 977.4; [[#A2|''Annals of Tigernach'' (2005)]] \u00a7 977.4; [[#B15|''Bodleian Library MS. Rawl. B. 488'' (n.d.)]].</ref> Cin\u00e1ed is recorded to have overseen an invasion of Cumbria during his reign.]]\n\nCuil\u00e9n seems to have been succeeded by his kinsman [[Cin\u00e1ed mac Ma\u00edl Choluim]].<ref>[[#B4|Broun (2004a)]]; [[#B7|Broun (2004c)]].</ref> One of the latter's first acts as [[King of Alba]] was evidently an invasion of the kingdom of the Cumbrians.<ref>[[#W10|Williams (2014)]]; [[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 25; [[#C7|Clarkson (2012a)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 30; [[#O2|Oram (2011)]] ch. 5; [[#W4|Woolf (2009)]] p. 259; [[#B13|Busse (2006a)]]; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 35; [[#B7|Broun (2004c)]].</ref> This campaign could well have been a retaliatory response to Cuil\u00e9n's killing,<ref name=\"W14-4;W4-259\">[[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 25; [[#W4|Woolf (2009)]] p. 259.</ref> carried out in the context of crushing a British affront to Scottish authority.<ref name=\"W14-4\">[[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 25.</ref> In any event, Cin\u00e1ed's invasion ended in defeat,<ref>[[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 35; [[#B7|Broun (2004c)]].</ref> a fact which coupled with Cuil\u00e9n's killing reveals that the Cumbrian realm was indeed a power to be reckoned with.<ref>[[#M4|McGuigan (2015b)]] p. 140; [[#C7|Clarkson (2012a)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 35; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 35.</ref> Whilst it is conceivable that Rhydderch could have succeeded Dyfnwal by the time of Cuil\u00e9n's fall,<ref>[[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 67 n. 66.</ref> another possibility is that Dyfnwal was still the king, and that Cin\u00e1ed's strike into Cumbrian territory was the last conflict of Dyfnwal's reign.<ref>[[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 35.</ref> In fact, it could have been at about this point when M\u00e1el Coluim took up the kingship.<ref>[[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] p. 44 n. 107.</ref> According to the ''Chronicle of the Kings of Alba'', Cin\u00e1ed constructed some sort of fortification on the [[River Forth]], perhaps the strategically located Fords of Frew near [[Stirling]].<ref>[[#M4|McGuigan (2015b)]] p. 149; [[#C7|Clarkson (2012a)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 30; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 37; [[#B6X|Broun (2007)]] p. 54; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] pp. 41\u201342; [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 147\u2013148, 147 n. 167; [[#H4|Hudson (1998)]] pp. 151, 161; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 96; [[#B6|Breeze (1992)]]; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 512; [[#S3|Skene (1867)]] p. 10.</ref> One possibility is that this engineering project was undertaken in the context of limiting Cumbrian incursions.<ref>[[#C7|Clarkson (2012a)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 30; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 37.</ref>\n\n==Amongst an assembly of kings==\n\n[[File:Dyfnwal ab Owain (British Library MS Cotton Faustina B IX, folio 9r).jpg|alt=Refer to caption|left|thumb|Dyfnwal's name as it appears on folio 9r of British Library Cotton Faustina B IX: \"{{lang|la|Dufnal}}{{-\"}}.<ref name=\"combine1\"/>]]\n\nThere is evidence to suggest that Dyfnwal was amongst the assembled kings who are [[King Edgar's council at Chester|recorded to have met]] with Edgar at [[Chester]] in 973.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 12; [[#E1|Edmonds (2014)]] p. 206; [[#W10|Williams (2014)]]; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] pp. 543\u2013544; [[#C7|Clarkson (2012a)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 29; [[#O2|Oram (2011)]] ch. 2; [[#W4|Woolf (2009)]] p. 259; [[#BXX5|Breeze (2007)]] pp. 154\u2013155; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] pp. 124, 167; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 208; [[#M3|Macquarrie (2004b)]]; [[#W11|Williams (2004a)]]; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] p. 42; [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] p. 143; [[#J2|Jayakumar (2002)]] p. 34; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] pp. 54\u201355, 67; [[#W5|Williams (1999)]] p. 88; [[#M2|Macquarrie (1998)]] p. 16; [[#W16|Williams; Smyth; Kirby (1991)]] pp. 104, 124; [[#S8|Stenton (1963)]] p. 324.</ref> According to the \"D\", \"[[Peterborough Chronicle|E]]\", and \"F\" versions of the ''Anglo-Saxon Chronicle'', after having been consecrated king that year, this English monarch assembled a massive naval force and met with six kings at Chester.<ref>[[#F9|Firth (2018)]] p. 48; [[#H10|Holland (2016)]] ch. Malmesbury \u00b6 6; [[#M4|McGuigan (2015b)]] pp. 143\u2013144, 144 n. 466; [[#M5|Molyneaux (2015)]] p. 34; [[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6\u00b6 9\u201310, 7 n. 11; [[#W10|Williams (2014)]]; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] pp. 543\u2013544; [[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 30; [[#M7|Molyneaux (2011)]] pp. 66, 69, 88; [[#BXX5|Breeze (2007)]] p. 153; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] p. 124; [[#M9|Matthews (2007)]] p. 10; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] pp. 207\u2013208; [[#F4|Forte; Oram; Pedersen (2005)]] p. 218; [[#IX1|Irvine (2004)]] p. 59; [[#K3|Karkov (2004)]] p. 108; [[#W11|Williams (2004a)]]; [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 138, 140, 140 n. 140, 144; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 50; [[#XB103|Baker (2000)]] pp. 83\u201384; [[#W5|Williams (1999)]] pp. 88, 116, 191 n. 50; [[#W9|Whitelock (1996)]] pp. 229\u2013230; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 97; [[#S8|Stenton (1963)]] p. 364; [[#A5|Anderson, AO (1908)]] pp. 75\u201376; [[#S12|Stevenson, WH (1898)]]; [[#T6|Thorpe (1861)]] pp. 225\u2013227.</ref> By the tenth century, the number of kings who met with him was alleged to have been eight, as evidenced by the tenth-century ''Life of St Swithun''.<ref>[[#E2|Edmonds (2015)]] p. 61 n. 94; [[#K2|Keynes (2015)]] pp. 113\u2013114; [[#M4|McGuigan (2015b)]] pp. 143\u2013144; [[#E1|Edmonds (2014)]] p. 206, 206 n. 60; [[#W10|Williams (2014)]]; [[#M7|Molyneaux (2011)]] p. 67; [[#BXX5|Breeze (2007)]] p. 154; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] p. 124; [[#M9|Matthews (2007)]] p. 10; [[#K3|Karkov (2004)]] p. 108; [[#W11|Williams (2004a)]]; [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 140\u2013141, 141 n. 145, 145; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 51; [[#W5|Williams (1999)]] pp. 191 n. 50, 203 n. 71; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] pp. 97\u201398; [[#J1|Jennings (1994)]] pp. 213\u2013214; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 479 n. 1; [[#S12|Stevenson, WH (1898)]]; [[#SA1|Skeat (1881)]] pp. 468\u2013469.</ref> By the twelfth century, the eight kings began to be named and were alleged to have rowed Edgar down the [[River Dee, Cumbria|River Dee]], as evidenced by sources such as the twelfth-century texts ''[[Chronicon ex chronicis]]'',<ref>[[#F9|Firth (2018)]] p. 48; [[#E2|Edmonds (2015)]] p. 61 n. 94; [[#M4|McGuigan (2015b)]] pp. 143\u2013144, n. 466; [[#K2|Keynes (2015)]] p. 114; [[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6\u00b6 12\u201314; [[#E1|Edmonds (2014)]] p. 206; [[#W10|Williams (2014)]]; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] pp. 543\u2013544; [[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 30; [[#M7|Molyneaux (2011)]] pp. 66\u201367; [[#BXX5|Breeze (2007)]] p. 153; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] p. 124; [[#M9|Matthews (2007)]] p. 11; [[#F4|Forte; Oram; Pedersen (2005)]] p. 218; [[#K3|Karkov (2004)]] p. 108; [[#W11|Williams (2004a)]]; [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 13, 134, 134 n. 111, 142, 145; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] pp. 57\u201358; [[#W5|Williams (1999)]] pp. 116, 191 n. 50; [[#W9|Whitelock (1996)]] p. 230 n. 1; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 97; [[#J1|Jennings (1994)]] p. 213; [[#S9|Smyth (1989)]] pp. 226\u2013227; [[#S8|Stenton (1963)]] p. 364; [[#A5|Anderson, AO (1908)]] pp. 76\u201377; [[#S12|Stevenson, WH (1898)]]; [[#F1|Forester (1854)]] pp. 104\u2013105; [[#SA2|Stevenson, J (1853)]] pp. 247\u2013248; [[#T7|Thorpe (1848)]] pp. 142\u2013143.</ref> ''[[Gesta regum Anglorum]]'',<ref>[[#E2|Edmonds (2015)]] p. 61 n. 94; [[#K2|Keynes (2015)]] p. 114; [[#M4|McGuigan (2015b)]] p. 144, n. 466; [[#E1|Edmonds (2014)]] p. 206; [[#W10|Williams (2014)]]; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] pp. 543\u2013544; [[#M7|Molyneaux (2011)]] pp. 66\u201367; [[#BXX5|Breeze (2007)]] p. 153; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] p. 124; [[#M9|Matthews (2007)]] pp. 10\u201311; [[#K3|Karkov (2004)]] p. 108, 108 n. 123; [[#W11|Williams (2004a)]]; [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 143, 145; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] pp. 59\u201360; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 97; [[#A5|Anderson, AO (1908)]] p. 77 n. 1; [[#S12|Stevenson, WH (1898)]]; [[#G4|Giles (1847)]] p. 147 bk. 2 ch. 8; [[#H7|Hardy (1840)]] p. 236 bk. 2 ch. 148.</ref> and ''[[De primo Saxonum adventu]]'',<ref>[[#M4|McGuigan (2015b)]] p. 144, 144 n. 469; [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] p. 142, 142 n. 149, 145; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] pp. 60\u201361; [[#A5|Anderson, AO (1908)]] p. 76 n. 2; [[#AA2|Arnold (1885)]] p. 372.</ref> as well as the thirteenth-century ''[[Chronica majora]]'',<ref>[[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 60; [[#LA1|Luard (1872)]] pp. 466\u2013467.</ref> and both the Wendover<ref>[[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 60; [[#G3|Giles (1849)]] pp. 263\u2013264; [[#C5|Coxe (1841)]] p. 415.</ref> and Paris versions of ''Flores historiarum''.<ref>[[#L1|Luard (2012)]] p. 513; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 60; [[#Y1|Yonge (1853)]] p. 484.</ref> One of the names in all these sources\u2014specifically identified as a Welsh king by ''Gesta regum Anglorum'', ''Chronica majora'', and both versions of ''Flores historiarum''\u2014appears to refer to Dyfnwal.<ref>[[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] pp. 543\u2013544; [[#L1|Luard (2012)]] p. 513; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] pp. 66\u201367; [[#A5|Anderson, AO (1908)]] p. 77 n. 1; [[#LA1|Luard (1872)]] pp. 466\u2013467; [[#Y1|Yonge (1853)]] p. 484; [[#G3|Giles (1849)]] pp. 263\u2013264; [[#G4|Giles (1847)]] p. 147 bk. 2 ch. 8; [[#C5|Coxe (1841)]] p. 415; [[#H7|Hardy (1840)]] p. 236 bk. 2 ch. 148.</ref> Another named figure, styled King of the Cumbrians, seems to be identical to his son, M\u00e1el Coluim.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 12; [[#E1|Edmonds (2014)]] p. 206; [[#W10|Williams (2014)]]; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] pp. 543\u2013544; [[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6\u00b6 30, 36; [[#C7|Clarkson (2012a)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 29; [[#M10|Minard (2012)]]; [[#AX1|Aird (2009)]] p. 309; [[#BXX5|Breeze (2007)]] pp. 154\u2013155; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] p. 167; [[#M6|Minard (2006)]]; [[#M3|Macquarrie (2004b)]]; [[#W11|Williams (2004a)]]; [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 142\u2013143; [[#D2|Duncan (2002)]] p. 23 n. 53; [[#J2|Jayakumar (2002)]] p. 34; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] pp. 66\u201367; [[#W5|Williams (1999)]] p. 116; [[#M2|Macquarrie (1998)]] p. 16; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 174 n. 9; [[#J1|Jennings (1994)]] p. 215; [[#W16|Williams; Smyth; Kirby (1991)]] pp. 104, 124; [[#S8|Stenton (1963)]] p. 324.</ref>{{#tag:ref|Both versions of ''Flores historiarum'' and ''Chronica majora'' specifically associate Dyfnwal with the [[Kingdom of Dyfed]].<ref>[[#L1|Luard (2012)]] p. 513; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 67; [[#LA1|Luard (1872)]] pp. 466\u2013467; [[#Y1|Yonge (1853)]] p. 484; [[#G3|Giles (1849)]] pp. 263\u2013264; [[#C5|Coxe (1841)]] p. 415.</ref> Another source linking Dyfnwal and M\u00e1el Coluim to the assembly is the ''Chronicle of Melrose''.<ref>[[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] p. 42; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] pp. 478\u2013479; [[#S1|Stevenson, J (1856)]] p. 100; [[#S4|Stevenson, J (1835)]] p. 34.</ref> If it was not Dyfnwal who attended the assembly, another possibility is that the like-named attendee was [[Domnall ua N\u00e9ill, King of Tara]].<ref>[[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 146\u2013147.</ref>|group=note}}\n\n[[File:Edgar, King of the English, rowed on the River Dee.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Black and white illustration of a king being rowed down a river in a rowboat by eight other kings|An early twentieth-century depiction of Edgar being rowed down the [[River Dee, Cumbria|River Dee]] by eight kings.<ref>[[#C2|''Cassell's History of England'' (1909)]] p. 53.</ref> According to the ''Anglo-Saxon Chronicle'', Edgar [[King Edgar's council at Chester|met six kings at Chester]]. By the twelfth century, chroniclers alleged that eight kings rowed Edgar down the river in an act of submission.<ref>[[#W11|Williams (2004a)]].</ref> One of these eight was Dyfnwal himself.]]\n\nWhilst the symbolic tale of the men rowing Edgar down the river may be an unhistorical embellishment, most of the names accorded to the eight kings can be associated with contemporary rulers, suggesting that some of these men may have taken part in a concord with him.<ref>[[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 74.</ref>{{#tag:ref|Two of the kings are accorded names are of uncertain meaning.<ref>[[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] pp. 67\u201374.</ref>|group=note}} Although the latter accounts allege that the kings submitted to Edgar, the ''Anglo-Saxon Chronicle'' merely states that they came to an agreement of cooperation with him, and thus became his {{lang|ang|efen-wyrhtan}} (\"co-workers\", \"even-workers\", \"fellow-workers\").<ref>[[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 66\u201367, 140; [[#D10|Davidson (2001)]] p. 208; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 77\u201378.</ref> One possibility is that the assembly somehow relates to Edmund's attested incursion into Cumbria in 945. According to the same source, when Edmund {{lang|ang|let}} Cumbria to M\u00e1el Coluim mac Domnaill, he had done so on the condition that the latter would be his {{lang|ang|mid-wyrhta}} (\"co-worker\", \"even-worker\", \"fellow-worker\", \"together-wright\").<ref>[[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] p. 16 n. 35; [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 115\u2013116, 140; [[#D10|Davidson (2001)]] p. 208; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] pp. 77\u201378; [[#W9|Whitelock (1996)]] p. 224; [[#A5|Anderson, AO (1908)]] p. 74; [[#T6|Thorpe (1861)]] pp. 212\u2013213.</ref> Less reliable non-contemporary sources such as ''De primo Saxonum adventu'',<ref>[[#KB1|Keynes (2008)]] p. 51; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 211; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] pp. 65\u201366; [[#A6|Anderson, MO (1960)]] p. 104; [[#A5|Anderson, AO (1908)]] p. 77; [[#AA2|Arnold (1885)]] p. 382.</ref> both the Wendover<ref>[[#A6|Anderson, MO (1960)]] p. 107, 107 n. 1; [[#G3|Giles (1849)]] p. 264; [[#C5|Coxe (1841)]] p. 416.</ref> and Paris versions of ''Flores historiarum'',<ref>[[#L1|Luard (2012)]] p. 513; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] pp. 65\u201366; [[#A6|Anderson, MO (1960)]] p. 107, 107 n. 1; [[#Y1|Yonge (1853)]] p. 485.</ref> and ''Chronica majora'' allege that Edgar granted [[Lothian]] to Cin\u00e1ed in 975.<ref>[[#A6|Anderson, MO (1960)]] p. 107, 107 nn. 1, 4; [[#A5|Anderson, AO (1908)]] pp. 77\u201378 n. 6; [[#LA1|Luard (1872)]] pp. 467\u2013468.</ref> If this supposed grant formed a part of the episode at Chester, it along with the concord of 945 could indicate that the assembly of 975 was not a submission as such, but more of a conference concerning mutual cooperation along the English borderlands.<ref>[[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] p. 125; [[#W11|Williams (2004a)]]; [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] p. 5; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] pp. 78\u201379.</ref> The location of the assembly of 973 at Chester would have been a logical neutral site for all parties.<ref>[[#B9|Barrow (2001)]] p. 89.</ref>{{#tag:ref|At about the same time as the assembly, ''De primo Saxonum adventu'' also notes that Edgar partitioned the Northumbrian ealdormanry into northern and southern divisions, split between the [[River Tees|Tees]] and {{lang|la|Myreforth}}. If the latter location refers to the [[mud flats]] between the [[River Esk, Cumbria|River Esk]] and the Solway Firth,<ref>[[#M4|McGuigan (2015b)]] p. 147; [[#AX1|Aird (2009)]] p. 309; [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] p. 149, 149 n. 172; [[#D2|Duncan (2002)]] p. 24; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 140; [[#A5|Anderson, AO (1908)]] p. 77; [[#AA2|Arnold (1885)]] p. 382.</ref> it would reveal that what is today Cumberland had fallen outwith Cumbrian royal authority and into the hands of the English.<ref>[[#D2|Duncan (2002)]] pp. 24\u201325.</ref>|group=note}}\n\n[[File:Edgar (British Library Cotton MS Tiberius B I, folio 142v).jpg|alt=Refer to caption|left|thumb|The name of Edgar as it appears on folio 142v of British Library Cotton Tiberius B I (the \"C\" version of the ''Anglo-Saxon Chronicle''): \"{{lang|ang|Eadgar Angla cing}}\".<ref>[[#O1|O'Keeffe (2001)]] p. 81; [[#W9|Whitelock (1996)]] p. 230; [[#T6|Thorpe (1861)]] p. 226; [[#C6|''Cotton MS Tiberius B I'' (n.d.)]].</ref>]]\n\nOne of the other named kings was Cin\u00e1ed.<ref>[[#AX1|Aird (2009)]] p. 309; [[#W4|Woolf (2009)]] p. 259; [[#BXX5|Breeze (2007)]] p. 155; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] p. 124; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 208; [[#B7|Broun (2004c)]]; [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] p. 142.</ref> Considering the fact that the ''Anglo-Saxon Chronicle'' numbers the kings at six, if Cin\u00e1ed was indeed present, it is unlikely that his rival, Cuil\u00e9n's brother [[Amla\u00edb, King of Scotland|Amla\u00edb mac Illuilb]], was also in attendance.<ref name=\"W1-208\">[[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 208.</ref> Although the chronology concerning the reigns of Cin\u00e1ed and Amla\u00edb mac Illuilb is uncertain<ref>[[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] pp. 208\u2013209.</ref>\u2014with Amla\u00edb mac Illuilb perhaps reigning from 971/976\u2013977<ref>[[#D2|Duncan (2002)]] pp. 21\u201322; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 93.</ref> and Cin\u00e1ed from 971/977\u2013995<ref name=\"W1-208\"/>\u2014the part played by the King of Alba at the assembly could well have concerned the frontier of his realm.<ref name=\"M9-25\">[[#M9|Matthews (2007)]] p. 25.</ref> One of the other named kings seems to have been [[Maccus mac Arailt]],<ref>[[#J3|Jennings (2015)]]; [[#W15|Wadden (2015)]] pp. 27\u201328; [[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 12; [[#W10|Williams (2014)]]; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] p. 543; [[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 31; [[#AX1|Aird (2009)]] p. 309; [[#W4|Woolf (2009)]] p. 259; [[#BXX5|Breeze (2007)]] p. 155; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] pp. 124\u2013125, 167, 222; [[#M9|Matthews (2007)]] p. 25; [[#F4|Forte; Oram; Pedersen (2005)]] p. 218; [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 143, 146, 151; [[#J2|Jayakumar (2002)]] p. 34; [[#W5|Williams (1999)]] p. 116; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 97; [[#J1|Jennings (1994)]] pp. 213\u2013214; [[#S8|Stenton (1963)]] p. 364.</ref> whilst another could have been this man's brother, [[Gofraid mac Arailt|Gofraid]].<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 12; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] p. 544; [[#BXX5|Breeze (2007)]] p. 156; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] pp. 125 n. 10, 222; [[#M9|Matthews (2007)]] p. 25; [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 143, 146, 151; [[#J2|Jayakumar (2002)]] p. 34.</ref> These two [[Kingdom of the Isles|Islesmen]] may have been regarded a threats by the Scots<ref name=\"M9-25\"/> and Cumbrians.<ref name=\"W1-208\"/> Maccus and Gofraid are recorded to have devastated [[Anglesey]] at the beginning of the decade,<ref>[[#G1|Gough-Cooper (2015b)]] p. 43 \u00a7 b993.1; [[#W10|Williams (2014)]]; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] p. 190; [[#M9|Matthews (2007)]] pp. 9, 25; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] pp. 206\u2013207; [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] p. 151; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] pp. 478\u2013479 n. 6; [[#R1|Rh\u0177s (1890)]] p. 262; [[#W7|Williams Ab Ithel (1860)]] pp. 24\u201325.</ref> which could indicate that Edgar's assembly was undertaken as a means to counter the menace posed by these energetic insular Scandinavians.<ref>[[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] p. 545; [[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] pp. 222\u2013223; [[#M9|Matthews (2007)]] pp. 9, 15; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] pp. 207\u2013208.</ref> In fact, there is evidence to suggest that, as a consequence of the assembly at Chester, the brothers may have turned their attention from the [[Great Britain|British mainland]] westwards towards [[Ireland]].<ref>[[#DZZ1|Downham (2007)]] pp. 126\u2013127, 222\u2013223; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 208.</ref>\n\n[[File:Thored Gunnerson (British Library Cotton MS Domitian A VIII, folio 58v).jpg|right|thumb|alt=Refer to caption|The name of [[Thored Gunnerson]] as it appears on folio 58v of British Library Cotton Domitian A VIII (the \"F\" version of the ''Anglo-Saxon Chronicle''): \"{{lang|la|Thored filius Gunnerses}}\".<ref>[[#XB103|Baker (2000)]] p. 83; [[#C13|''Cotton MS Domitian A VIII'' (n.d.)]].</ref>]]\n\nAnother aspect of the assembly may have concerned the remarkable rising power of Amla\u00edb C\u00faar\u00e1n in Ireland.<ref>[[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] p. 545; [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] p. 147.</ref> Edgar may have wished to not only reign in men such as Maccus and Gofraid, but prevent them\u2014and the Scots and Cumbrians\u2014from affiliating themselves with Amla\u00edb C\u00faar\u00e1n, and recognising the latter's authority in the Irish Sea region.<ref>[[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] p. 545.</ref> Another factor concerning Edgar, and his Scottish and Cumbrian counterparts, may have been the stability of the northern English frontier. For example, a certain [[Thored Gunnerson]] is recorded to have ravaged [[Westmorland]] in 966, an action that may have been undertaken by the English in the context of a response to Cumbrian southward expansion.<ref>[[#W10|Williams (2014)]]; [[#W11|Williams (2004a)]]; [[#W9|Whitelock (1996)]] p. 229; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 472; [[#T6|Thorpe (1861)]] p. 223.</ref>{{#tag:ref|According to the ''Life of St Cathr\u00f3e'', when Dyfnwal escorted Cathr\u00f3e to the frontier of his realm, the latter was then escorted by a certain Gunderic to the domain of Erich in York.<ref>[[#M4|McGuigan (2015b)]] p. 98; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 441; [[#S3|Skene (1867)]] p. 116; [[#C4|Colganvm (1645)]] p. 497 \u00a7 xvii.</ref> It is possible that Gunderic is identical to Thored's father, and identical to the Gunner who appears is charter evidence from 931\u2013963.<ref>[[#M4|McGuigan (2015b)]] pp. 98\u201399.</ref>|group=note}} Although the Scottish invasion of Cumbrian and English territory unleashed after Cin\u00e1ed's inauguration could have been intended to tackle Cumbrian opposition,<ref name=\"W14-4;W4-259\"/> another possibility is that the campaign may have been executed as a way to counter any occupation of Cumbrian territories by Thored.<ref>[[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 26.</ref>\n\n==Death and descendants==\n\n[[File:Dyfnwal ab Owain (Oxford Bodleian Library MS Rawlinson B 489, folio 33v).jpg|thumb|left|alt=Refer to caption|Dyfnwal's title as it appears on folio 33v of Oxford Bodleian Library Rawlinson B 489.<ref>[[#T2|''The Annals of Ulster'' (2017)]] \u00a7 975.2; [[#T1|''The Annals of Ulster'' (2008)]] 975.2; [[#B14|''Bodleian Library MS. Rawl. B. 489'' (n.d.)]].</ref> Irish sources accord him the title {{lang|mga|r\u00ed Bretan}} (\"King of the Britons\").<ref>[[#E1|Edmonds (2014)]] p. 208; [[#B6X|Broun (2007)]] p. 94 n. 62; [[#B12|Busse (2006c)]].</ref>]]\n\nBoth Dyfnwal<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 17; [[#W10|Williams (2014)]]; [[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6\u00b6 30, 36; [[#M10|Minard (2012)]]; [[#O2|Oram (2011)]] ch. 2; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 41; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 184; [[#B12|Busse (2006c)]]; [[#M6|Minard (2006)]]; [[#B11|Broun (2004d)]] pp. 128\u2013129; [[#M3|Macquarrie (2004b)]]; [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 39, 146; [[#M2|Macquarrie (1998)]] pp. 15\u201316; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] pp. 101, 174 n. 8; [[#W16|Williams; Smyth; Kirby (1991)]] p. 104.</ref> and his English counterpart died in 975.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 17; [[#W10|Williams (2014)]]; [[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 35; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 41; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 208; [[#W16|Williams; Smyth; Kirby (1991)]] p. 124.</ref> According to various [[Irish annals]], which style Dyfnwal King of the Britons, he met his end whilst undertaking a pilgrimage.<ref>[[#T2|''The Annals of Ulster'' (2017)]] \u00a7 975.2; [[#T3|''The Annals of Tigernach'' (2016)]] \u00a7 975.3; [[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 17, 7 n. 19; [[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 36; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 41; [[#T1|''The Annals of Ulster'' (2008)]] \u00a7 975.2; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 184; [[#A2|''Annals of Tigernach'' (2005)]] \u00a7 975.3; [[#B11|Broun (2004d)]] pp. 128\u2013129; [[#M3|Macquarrie (2004b)]]; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] p. 42; [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 39, 146; [[#M2|Macquarrie (1998)]] pp. 15\u201316; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 174 n. 8; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 480, 480 n. 7.</ref> These sources are corroborated by Welsh texts such as the thirteenth- and fourteenth-century ''[[Brenhinedd y Saesson]]'',<ref>[[#M9|Matthews (2007)]] p. 25; [[#JA1|Jones; Williams; Pughe (1870)]] p. 658.</ref> and ''Brut y Tywysogyon'', with the latter stating that Dyfnwal died in [[Rome]] having received the [[tonsure]].<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 17, 7 n. 19; [[#C16|Clancy (2002)]] p. 22; [[#M2|Macquarrie (1998)]] pp. 15\u201316; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 174 n. 8; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 480; [[#R1|Rh\u0177s (1890)]] p. 262; [[#W7|Williams Ab Ithel (1860)]] pp. 26\u201327.</ref> Such religious retirement late in the life of a ruler was not uncommon amongst contemporaries. For example, Custant\u00edn evidently became a monk upon his own abdication, whilst Amla\u00edb C\u00faar\u00e1n retired to the holy island of [[Iona]] in pilgrimage.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 17; [[#C7|Clarkson (2012a)]] ch. 10 \u00b6 27.</ref> One possibility is that Dyfnwal decided to undertake his religious journey\u2014or was perhaps forced to undertake it\u2014as a result of the violent actions of Rhydderch.<ref>[[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 36; [[#O2|Oram (2011)]] ch. 2.</ref>\n\n[[File:M\u00e1el Coluim mac Domnaill (Oxford Bodleian Library MS Rawlinson B 488, folio 15v) 2.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Refer to caption|The title of Dyfnwal's son, M\u00e1el Coluim, as it appears on folio 15v of Oxford Bodleian Library Rawlinson B 488: \"{{lang|mga|r\u00ed Bretan Tuaisceirt}}\" (\"king of the Britons of the north\").<ref>[[#T3|''The Annals of Tigernach'' (2016)]] \u00a7 997.3; [[#A2|''Annals of Tigernach'' (2005)]] \u00a7 997.3; [[#B15|''Bodleian Library MS. Rawl. B. 488'' (n.d.)]].</ref>]]\n\nIt is conceivable that Dyfnwal was still reigning in 973,<ref>[[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 30; [[#B12|Busse (2006c)]]; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 55.</ref> and that it was Edgar's death two years later that precipitated the transfer of the kingship to Dyfnwal's son M\u00e1el Coluim, and contributed to Dyfnwal's pilgrimage to Rome. In fact, the upheaval caused by the absence of the English and Cumbrian kings could well have contributed to Cin\u00e1ed's final elimination of Amla\u00edb mac Illuilb in 997.<ref name=\"W1-208\"/> Another possibility is that M\u00e1el Coluim's part in the 973 assembly may have partly concerned his father's impending pilgrimage, and that he sought surety for Dyfnwal's safe passage through Edgar's realm.<ref name=\"M9-25\"/> The fact that M\u00e1el Coluim is identified as one of the assembled kings could indicate that Dyfnwal had relinquished control to him at some point before the convention.<ref>[[#W10|Williams (2014)]]; [[#W14|Walker (2013)]] ch. 4 \u00b6 30; [[#C7|Clarkson (2012a)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 29; [[#M3|Macquarrie (2004)]]; [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] p. 146; [[#W16|Williams; Smyth; Kirby (1991)]] p. 104.</ref> Evidence that he had indeed assumed the kingship may exist in the record of a certain ''Malcolm dux'' who witnessed an [[Anglo-Saxon charters|English royal charter]] in 970.<ref>[[#M4|McGuigan (2015b)]] p. 101, 101 n. 302; [[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 5, 7 n. 3; [[#BXX4|Birch (1893)]] pp. 557\u2013560 \u00a7 1266; [[#T1001|Thorpe (1865)]] pp. 237\u2013243; [[#M11|''Malcolm 4'' (n.d.)]]; [[#S7|''S 779'' (n.d.)]].</ref> Although the authenticity of this document is questionable, the attested Malcolm could well be identical to M\u00e1el Coluim himself.<ref>[[#M5|Molyneaux (2015)]] p. 57 n. 45; [[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 5; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] p. 544; [[#M7|Molyneaux (2011)]] p. 66; [[#KB1|Keynes (2008)]] p. 50 n. 232; [[#D11|Davidson (2002)]] pp. 147, 147 n. 166, 152; [[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 71; [[#H2|Hudson (1994)]] p. 174 n. 9.</ref>{{#tag:ref|This charter is composed of Latin and Old English text. The document may be evidence of Scottish and Cumbrian submission to the English. For example, one place the text reads in Latin: \"I, Edgar, ruler of the beloved island of Albion, subjected to us of the rule of the Scots and Cumbrians and the Britons and of all regions round about ...\". The corresponding Old English text reads: \"I, Edgar, exalted as king over the English people by His [God's] grace, and He has now subjected to my authority the Scots and Cumbrians and also the Britons and all that this island has inside ...\".<ref>[[#T5|Thornton (2001)]] p. 52, 52 n. 6; [[#BXX4|Birch (1893)]] pp. 557\u2013560 \u00a7 1266; [[#T1001|Thorpe (1865)]] pp. 237\u2013243; [[#S7|''S 779'' (n.d.)]].</ref>|group=note}} If M\u00e1el Coluim was indeed king in 973, Dyfnwal's role at the assembly may have been that of an '[[Diplomat|elder statesman]]' of sorts\u2014possibly serving as an adviser or mentor\u2014especially considering his decades of experience in international affairs.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 12; [[#C7|Clarkson (2012a)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 29; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 35.</ref> The fact that he left his realm for Rome could be evidence that he did not regard his realm or dynasty to be threatened during his absence.<ref>[[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] p. 42.</ref>\n\n[[File:Owain ap Dyfnwal (Oxford Bodleian Library MS Jesus College 111, folio 60r).jpg|thumb|left|alt=Refer to caption|The name of Dyfnwal's apparent son, [[Owain ap Dyfnwal (died 1015)|Owain]], as it appears on folio 60r of Oxford Jesus College 111: \"{{lang|wlm|owein}}\".<ref>[[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 550 n. 2; [[#R1|Rh\u0177s (1890)]] p. 264; [[#W7|Williams Ab Ithel (1860)]] pp. 34\u201335; [[#J5|''Jesus College MS. 111'' (n.d.)]]; [[#O5|''Oxford Jesus College MS. 111'' (n.d.)]].</ref> This source records the latter's death in 1015.]]\n\nSurviving sources fail to note the Cumbrian kingdom between the obituaries of Dyfnwal in 975 and his son, M\u00e1el Coluim, in 997.<ref>[[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 41.</ref> There is reason to suspect that Dyfnwal had another son, Owain, who reigned after M\u00e1el Coluim.<ref name=\"Owain1\">[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 7 \u00b6 17; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 9 \u00b6 41; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] pp. 222, 233, 236.</ref> For instance, according to the \"B\" version of ''Annales Cambri\u00e6'', a certain Owain\u2014identified as the son of a man named Dyfnwal\u2014was slain in 1015.<ref>[[#G1|Gough-Cooper (2015b)]] p. 46 \u00a7 b1036.1; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] p. 572 fig. 17.4; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 236; [[#B11|Broun (2004d)]] p. 128, 128 n. 66; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] p. 43; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 550.</ref> This obituary is corroborated by ''Brut y Tywysogyon'',<ref>[[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] p. 572 fig. 17.4; [[#B11|Broun (2004d)]] p. 128 n. 66; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] p. 44 n. 107; [[#A1|Anderson, AO (1922)]] p. 550 n. 2; [[#R1|Rh\u0177s (1890)]] p. 264; [[#W7|Williams Ab Ithel (1860)]] pp. 34\u201335.</ref> and ''Brenhinedd y Saesson''.<ref>[[#B11|Broun (2004d)]] p. 128 n. 66; [[#JA1|Jones; Williams; Pughe (1870)]] p. 660.</ref> Although it may be possible that the record of this man's death refers to [[Owain Foel, King of Strathclyde]],<ref>[[#B11|Broun (2004d)]] p. 128 n. 66; [[#M2|Macquarrie (1998)]] pp. 16\u201317.</ref> there is no reason to disregard the obituaries as erroneous. If the like-named men are indeed different people, they could well have been closely related. Whilst the former may have been a son of Dyfnwal himself, the latter could well have been a son of Dyfnwal's son, M\u00e1el Coluim.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. genealogical tables; [[#C10|Charles-Edwards (2013b)]] p. 572 fig. 17.4; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. genealogical tables; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] pp. 236, 238 tab. 6.4; [[#B11|Broun (2004d)]] pp. 128 n. 66, 135 tab.; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] p. 44, 44 n. 107; [[#D2|Duncan (2002)]] pp. 29, 41.</ref> The Owain who died in 1015, therefore, would seem to have assumed the Cumbrian kingship after M\u00e1el Coluim's death in 997, and would appear to have reigned into the early eleventh century before Owain Foel's assumption of the throne.<ref name=\"Owain1\"/>\n\n[[File:Cairn of Dunmail Raise.JPG|thumb|right|alt=Refer to caption|The [[cairn]] of [[Dunmail Raise]] lying between the [[dual carriageways]] of the [[A591 road]].]]\n\nDyfnwal may be the man immortalised in the name of a [[mountain pass]] in the [[Lake District]] known as [[Dunmail Raise]] (meaning \"Dyfnwal's Cairn\").<ref>[[#C1|Cannon (2015)]]; [[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 \u00b6\u00b6 22\u201327; [[#C3|Clarkson (2010)]] ch. 10 \u00b6 11; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] pp. 42, 216; [[#W2|Winchester (2000)]] pp. 33\u201334.</ref> According to popular legend, a local king named Dunmail was slain by [[Anglo-Saxons|Saxons]] on the pass and buried beneath a [[cairn]]. Forms of this tradition may date to about the sixteenth century,<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 \u00b6\u00b6 22\u201327.</ref> as the place name is first marked on a map dating to 1576.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 \u00b6 24; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] p. 43 n. 103.</ref> By the end of the seventeenth century, it was claimed that the place name marked the site of \"a great heap of Stones call'd Dunmail-Raise-Stones, suppos'd to have been cast up by Dunmail K. of Cumberland for the Bounds of his Kingdom\".<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 \u00b6 24; [[#OZZZ1|Ogilby (1699)]] p. 179.</ref> Forms of the tale began to appear in print in the following century. In time, the ever-evolving legend became associated with the events of 945.<ref>[[#C14|Clarkson (2014)]] ch. 6 \u00b6 24.</ref> The cairn itself lies between the [[dual carriageways]] of the [[A591 road]].<ref>[[#P1|Pugmire (2004)]] pp. 112, 115 fig. 2; [[#W2|Winchester (2000)]] pp. 33\u201334.</ref> It seems to have marked an old boundary between Westmorland and Cumberland, and might have also marked the southern territorial extent of the Cumbrian kingdom.<ref>[[#W2|Winchester (2000)]] pp. 33\u201334.</ref> Nevertheless, the site's alleged importance in the early mediaeval period cannot be proven.<ref>[[#E2|Edmonds (2015)]] p. 54.</ref> Other place names that may be named after Dyfnwal include [[Cardonald]] ({{gbmapping|NS5364}}),<ref>[[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] pp. 60, 147, 147 n. 20.</ref> and [[Dundonald, South Ayrshire|Dundonald]]/[[Dundonald Castle]] ({{gbmapping|NS3636034517}}).<ref>[[#E5|Ewart; Pringle; Caldwell et al. (2004)]] p. 7; [[#H3|Hicks (2003)]] p. 60.</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==Citations==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==References==\n\n===Primary sources===\n{{refbegin|colwidth=30em}}\n* {{cite book |year=1908 |editor1-last=Anderson |editor1-first=AO |editor1-link=Alan Orr Anderson |title=Scottish Annals from English Chroniclers, A.D. 500 to 1286 |url=https://archive.org/details/scottishannalsfr00andeuoft |publisher=[[David Nutt (publisher)|David Nutt]] |location=London |ol=7115802M |ref=A5 }}\n* {{cite book |year=1922 |editor1-last=Anderson |editor1-first=AO |title=Early Sources of Scottish History, A.D. 500 to 1286 |url=https://archive.org/details/cu31924028144313 |volume=1 |publisher=Oliver and Boyd |location=London |ol=14712679M |ref=A1 }}\n* {{cite journal |last=Anderson |first=AO |year=1930 |title=The Prophecy of Berchan |journal=[[Zeitschrift f\u00fcr